<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guards Said Set Up Prison Fights  </HEADLINE>
By KILEY RUSSELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- Eight guards at one of California's
toughest prisons abused their authority by staging gladiator-style
fights among rival inmates ''for entertainment purposes,'' a
prosecutor said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''To these defendants, inmate safety was a game,'' Assistant
U.S. Attorney Daniel Velez said in his closing argument to the
federal trial of the Corcoran State Prison guards. ''Rather than
protect the inmates, they used them for entertainment purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Four of the eight defendants face possible life sentences in the
shooting death of an inmate during a 1994 prison brawl. The other
four face lesser charges in connection with another fight.
</P>
<P>
   All eight guards have denied the accusations, and their lawyers
Tuesday began what is expected to be three days of arguments for
their acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 8{-week trial, prosecutors pointed to a
significant rise in prisoner fights during the defendants' daytime
shift.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are fighting one, two, three, four times a day within
an hour of each other ... and nobody said anything about it,''
Velez said.
</P>
<P>
   During a 2{-year period, there were 84 fights during the guards'
shift -- 300 percent more than the next most violent area of the
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The fights came to light in 1994 when two guards blew the
whistle on their colleagues after the death of inmate Preston Tate,
who was shot by a guard during one of the alleged set-up fights.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Christopher Bethea fired a round from his 9mm rifle in
an attempt to wound a fighting prisoner and struck Tate in the
head, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Douglas Martin, Sgt. John Vaughn, officer Jerry Arvizu and
Bethea face life sentences if convicted of setting up the fight
that led to Tate's death.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Truman Jennings and officers Michael Gipson, Timothy
Dickerson, and Raul Tavarez face up to 10 years in connection with
another prison yard fight in February 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Velez said the guards knew the so-called Southern Mexicans and
black prisoners were warring and that the officers should have kept
them away from each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''Putting Southern Mexicans and blacks together is like putting
a flame to gun powder ... if you do it enough times, it eventually
will go off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers began closing arguments Tuesday by denying there
was a war between prison gangs at the time the guards are alleged
to have set up the fights.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vast, vast majority (of inmates) went out to yard without
any problems,'' said Arvizu's lawyer, William Portonova.
</P>
<P>
   The brawls can be blamed on the violent nature of the inmates,
which is what landed them in the high-security unit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The violence follows the inmates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the number of fights was greatest on the
defendants' watch was because it was the only shift when prisoners
were free, Portonova said.
</P>
<P>
   The prison system's ''integrated yard policy'' is partly to
blame for the violence, said Curtis Sisk, Jennings' lawyer. That
policy required prisoners to be placed in the yard together
regardless of racial background or geographic loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   The other defense lawyers will present closing arguments
Wednesday. The case is expected to go to the jury by Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
