<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: 'Personal watercraft' a $1 billion nuisance nationwide  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL GORMLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A national study used by opponents of
personal watercraft concludes that noise from Jet Skis is a $1
billion national problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only effective noise-control measure is banning Jet Skis
outright,'' said economist Charles Komanoff, co-author of the
report for the environmental lobbying group Noise Pollution
Clearinghouse based in Montpelier, Vt. The study also recommended
restricting the craft to a few designated areas.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year study used a formula to determine the value of
''lost enjoyment'' from the whine and roar of 1.3 million
watercraft often known by the trade name Jet Ski.
</P>
<P>
   The formula included comparison with the cost of known noise
abatement, like when airports buy houses in flight paths. The
report found Americans would be willing to pay $1 billion to rid
waters and beaches of the noise from Jet Skis.
</P>
<P>
   Using decibel measures, the study also contends that Jet Skis
create a more irritating noise than motor boats. That's because Jet
Skis frequently leave the water as they crest waves, so the motor
is no longer muffled by the water. Critics say that's why the craft
warrant special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The American Watercraft Association says their sport is under
attack by such lobbying efforts and is being discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
   ''At every level of government, our sport faces restrictions and
outright bans,'' states the national group on its Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   The group supports safety classes like ones now required in New
York state after a rise in accidents, some of them fatal. Members
of the association are also signing a code of ethics for safe and
courteous operation.
</P>
<P>
   A national spokeswoman didn't return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the group's New York spokesmen, Charles Bufano of Medford
on Long Island, said the noise concern is overblown. He said
outrage against the motorcycle-like power boats is loud, but from a
relatively few people who live along shores.
</P>
<P>
   The group's 11-point code of ethics includes: ''I will pay close
attention to the noise my vessel makes and be aware of how that
noise affects others on or near the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists in states like New York don't think that's enough.
</P>
<P>
   The report is being used to bolster an effort to pass a bill
that would give local governments the power to restrict or ban the
craft. The restrictions could limit time and speed and prohibit
''wave jumping'' and other behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jet Skis are a major threat to a lot of things - wildlife,
habitat - but they're also a threat to peace and quiet,'' said
David Higby of Environmental Advocates based in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has been approved by the Democrat-controlled
Assembly and has 13 Republican sponsors in the GOP-dominated
Senate, Higby said.
</P>
<P>
   Local businesses and some governments where marinas are riding
the vessels' wave of popularity have joined the industry opposition
to the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But even one of the American Watercraft Association's two New
York spokesmen says he's had enough of the noise and congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Bufano sold the Sea Doo he bought in 1991. Back
then on a typical day, he'd see a half-dozen fellow jet skiers. Now
he sees five dozen or more.
</P>
<P>
   That, Bufano said, is the noise problem. He also said the sport
is evolving to attract mostly young people, partly because of the
low cost of older, noisier craft. The Sea Doo he bought for $8,500
sold two weeks ago for $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ride by myself and you don't hear anything. You get a group
and it's annoying,'' said Bufano, 35. He said an increasing
minority of riders ride in groups, are discourteous and violate the
law that prohibits jetting around within 500 feet of shore.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, this has become a young boys' sport, which is
kind of ruining it for everyone else.'' Bufano said. ''There is a
very inexperienced crowd out there now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-07-00 0017 </TRAILER>
