<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Man Charged in Stabbing Death  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA WERNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Prosecutors charged a man with murder Tuesday
in the stabbing deaths of an elderly couple who were friends and
financial supporters of some of the city's top politicians and
sports figures.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the suspect, Steve Jackson, was a cocaine addict and
a former tenant of Albert and Edna Patton who had asked the pair
for money in the past and gotten it.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Michael Whelan said a bloody piece of clothing linked
to the murder victims by DNA testing was found in the motel room
where Jackson was taken into custody.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors found the bodies of Patton, 90, and the
wheelchair-bound Mrs. Patton, 85, in their home on May 27. They
were well-known philanthropists in their poor, largely minority
community, and Patton had co-founded the national 100 Black Men
organization for disadvantaged youth.
</P>
<P>
   Their home was filled with photos of them with such celebrities
as Wilt Chamberlain, Elgin Baylor, Muhammad Ali and Stevie Wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Police said a $25,000 reward the City Council authorized to help
find the Pattons' killers brought informants forward with
information that led them to Jackson, 35, who was taken into
custody Friday at a nearby motel where police said he'd been
staying for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who is being held without bail, is to be arraigned June
20.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charged him Tuesday with one count of first-degree
robbery and two counts of murder with special circumstances,
meaning he could face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Pattons were killed about 24 hours before Police Chief
Bernard C. Parks' 20-year-old granddaughter was shot to death
outside a fast-food restaurant two blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the slayings were not related and there have been no
developments in the search for Lori Gonzalez's killer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0023 </TRAILER>
