<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Judge Leads Chief Justice Vote  </HEADLINE>
By PHILLIP RAWLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- The Alabama judge who fought to keep the
Ten Commandments displayed in his courtroom won the Republican
primary for chief justice of the state Supreme Court on Tuesday and
avoided a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   With 86 percent of precincts reporting, Etowah County Circuit
Judge Roy Moore had 99,210 votes, or 56 percent. Supreme Court
Justice Harold See, who was backed by the GOP establishment, had
51,142 votes, or 29 percent. Two other judges split the rest.
</P>
<P>
   By getting more than 50 percent, Moore advanced to the general
election Nov. 7 against civil appeals court Judge Sharon Yates, a
Democrat who had no primary opposition Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, 53, said that if he becomes Alabama's top judge, he will
take the Ten Commandments to the State Judicial Building in
Montgomery. Appearing before cheering supporters in Gadsden, Moore
quoted Scripture as he explained why he ran stronger than polls had
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're about establishing the moral foundation of our law once
again in this state and in our country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   See had a $1.1 million campaign warchest -- more than twice as
much as his primary opponents combined. But Moore's Ten
Commandments fight gave him greater name recognition and clearly
helped him at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a Christian and I like his stand for the Ten Commandments
and family values,'' said Shea Hill, a 29-year-old mother of two
small children who wore a cross necklace when she went to vote in
Pelham.
</P>
<P>
   The current chief justice, Republican Perry Hooper, is retiring
because state law prohibits judges from running after they turn 70.
The race to replace Hooper took on extra significance because of
the GOP's 5-4 majority on the court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the American Civil Liberties Union sued Moore over his
display of the Ten Commandments and his having Christian ministers
open court sessions with prayer. Moore spoke about his case at
rallies around the country.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge threw out the suit, and then-Gov. Fob James and
the state attorney general filed their own lawsuit in hopes of
having Moore's courtroom practices declared constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Alabama Supreme Court dismissed the case because the state
officials and the judge were on the same side. But the court let
Moore have the plaque and the prayers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0046 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
