<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Data Sharing Regs Eyed  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Financial companies would have to get
customers' consent before sharing their medical data with other
firms or using it to make credit decisions, under a new proposal by
the head of the House Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation proposed Tuesday by Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, is
similar to the medical-data provisions of legislation pushed last
month by the Clinton administration and Democratic lawmakers. The
Democrats have promised to make the Clinton-Gore privacy proposal,
opposed by most Republicans and given little chance of passage, a
hot election-year issue.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals go beyond privacy rules included in sweeping
legislation, which President Clinton signed into law in November,
removing Depression-era barriers and allowing banks, brokerage
firms and insurers to get into each other's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Leach said his bill ''ensures privacy protection in an area of
great sensitivity to all Americans: personal health and medical
records.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that a consumer applying for a loan or credit card
from a bank, for example, shouldn't have to worry about getting
rejected because of medical data provided to the bank by an
insurance company with which it is affiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John LaFalce of New York, the Banking Committee's senior
Democrat, called Leach's proposal ''a constructive effort to
address the issue of medical privacy.'' But he said it does not go
far enough because it deals only with that issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore bill, which LaFalce sponsored in the House,
also would require financial companies to get customers' consent
before sharing with other firms lists of what they buy and where
they buy it -- a practice known as profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The banking industry, meanwhile, is divided over new voluntary
guidelines for protecting consumers' private data, including their
medical information.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines adopted by some major banking groups are similar
to privacy rules for all financial companies that became law last
fall, but two groups representing community banks believe they're
too strict and don't really apply to them. Smaller banks often rely
on marketing agreements with outside companies, and the guidelines
restrict sharing of customer data with outside firms.
</P>
<P>
   The community banks' opposition to the guidelines announced
Tuesday reflected a bitter schism between big financial
institutions involved in multiple businesses such as banking,
investments and insurance, on the one hand, and smaller banks and
thrifts that focus only on banking.
</P>
<P>
   ''Medical privacy is a major issue for Citigroup,'' Ken
Guenther, executive vice president of the Independent Community
Bankers of America, said in a telephone interview. ''It is not a
major issue for thousands and thousands of community banks, savings
and loans, and local insurance agents.''
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Citigroup, perhaps the best-known financial
conglomerate, combines under its corporate roof Citibank, the
Salomon Smith Barney securities and investment firm, and Travelers
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest push for financial services legislation last year
came from the larger financial companies, and their lobbyists
accepted the privacy restrictions as a condition for enactment of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary guidelines announced by the American Bankers
Association, the Consumer Bankers Association and the Financial
Services Roundtable include a prohibition against banks and savings
associations disclosing customers' medical data, or using such
information for marketing or credit decisions, without their
consent.
</P>
<P>
   Leach's proposal would:
</P>
<P>
   --Require financial companies to obtain customers' express
written consent before disclosing ''individually identifiable''
health or medical data to an affiliated company or any other firm,
such as a telemarketer.
</P>
<P>
   --Prohibit financial companies from using health or medical data
in deciding whether to grant credit without the prospective
borrower's express consent.
</P>
<P>
   --Require separate and specific customer consent for disclosure
of mental health information.
</P>
<P>
   --Give consumers the right to inspect, copy and correct their
health or medical data that are under the control of a financial
company.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   House Banking Committee's Web site: http://www.house.gov/banking
</P>
<P>
   American Bankers Association: http://www.aba.com
</P>
<P>
   Independent Community Bankers of America: http://www.icba.org
</P>
</TEXT>
