<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Economy Hurt by Hostage Crisis  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Fiji may seem like paradise on Earth, but it's
just now learning a painful financial lesson: Its white sand, coral
reefs and great surf can't outweigh the tourist turnoff of men with
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's economy -- based on tourism, sugar production and clothes
manufacturing -- has been frozen since armed rebels stormed
Parliament House on May 19 and took Prime Minister Mahendra
Chaudhry and most of his government hostage.
</P>
<P>
   In the five-star resorts dotting Fiji's island chain, the
poolside lounges are empty. In plantations, towering fields of
sugar cane are ripe but unharvested. In the clothes factories of
Suva, the capital, workers are sent home early each time they hear
rumors that a mob intent on a riot is headed for town.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just coming into the peak season and we should have been
full this week for sure,'' said Paul Southey, general manager of
the Centra Pacific Harbor, an 83-room resort nestled among coconut
palms on the Coral Coast 30 miles west of Suva. ''Instead, we have
35 percent occupancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost half a million tourists visited Fiji in 1999, mostly from
Australia, New Zealand and the United States. They spent around
$240 million on hotels and millions more on scuba diving, fishing
and boating tours, restaurants and other leisure activities, the
Fiji Bureau of Statistics says.
</P>
<P>
   But the nation is in the midst of a standoff that shows no sign
of ending, with rebel leader George Speight holding more than 30
people hostage and insisting he'll keep them until he gets to name
a new government.
</P>
<P>
   The military, which took control of Fiji a little more than week
into the crisis, is saying just as strongly that Speight and his
rebels can't have any power, although it has offered amnesty in
exchange for release of the captives.
</P>
<P>
   Speight claims he is acting on behalf of indigenous Fijians, and
wants the country's large minority of Indian descendants to be
barred from holding political power.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 19, the number of tourists arriving at Fiji's
international airport has dropped to 200 people a day.
</P>
<P>
   ''That should be 1,800 people a day,'' said Southey. ''Any
operator that tells you this crisis is not having an effect is
telling an untruth.''
</P>
<P>
   While cancellations in the past three weeks have skyrocketed,
Southey is more concerned about the lack of new bookings.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term damage will come from travel agencies cutting
their marketing campaigns for Fiji, which competes with a dozen
other nations as a ''Pacific paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond just tourism, business leaders and economists say Fiji's
whole economy is paralyzed and will likely remain so as long as
hostages are being held.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether that will carry over into long-term
trouble because of economic sanctions, which are being threatened
by Fiji's most important trading partners -- the European Union,
Australia and New Zealand -- unless democracy is quickly restored.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we have now is the worst possible thing for the Fiji
economy,'' said David Forsyth, head of the economics department at
the University of the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   With an annual gross domestic product of about $1.44 billion,
Fiji is heavily dependent on other countries for its prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Next to tourism, the two biggest industries are sugar, worth
around $120 million a year from exports, and clothes manufacturing,
worth about $48 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth warned that if the European Union abandons a trade
agreement under which it pays up to three times the market price
for sugar -- as it has threatened to do if any member of Speight's
group is included in a new government -- it will be catastrophic for
Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 25,000 cane farmers, mostly ethnic Indians, would be
unable to meet production costs and be forced off the land. Many of
the country's 2,000 seasonal cane cutters, mostly indigenous
Fijians, would lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   This year's crop is overdue for harvest, but farmers have
refused to do so until Chaudhry, Fiji's first Indian prime
minister, and the other hostages are released.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they do not harvest, everything will be lost, the economy
of Fiji will be lost,'' said Umesh Prasad, director of the
Sugarcane Growers' Association.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's garment industry has boomed since the early 1990s, when
Australia agreed to give preferential treatment to its imports.
</P>
<P>
   If Australia cancels the agreement, foreign manufacturers that
flooded in will move away, taking up to 20,000 jobs with them,
Forsyth said.
</P>
<P>
   Speight says he expects an international backlash against his
coup, but that sanctions and economic and diplomatic isolation are
a price indigenous Fijians are willing to pay for political power.
</P>
<P>
   Politics aside, Forsyth said, the economy's best hope would be
for the military rulers to quickly re-establish order. The sugar
and garment industries could recover if international sanctions can
be avoided, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0109 </TRAILER>
