<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Settlers' Fears Grow  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARME TSUR, West Bank (AP) -- Small and remote, this red-roofed
Jewish settlement and others like it lie at the heart of what could
be a risky new peace push by Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the Israeli leader is speaking openly about
the prospect of leaving 50,000 Jewish settlers -- one-quarter of
those living in the West Bank and Gaza Strip -- outside the umbrella
of Israeli sovereignty as part of an accord with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   And in the isolated communities likely to be sacrificed under
this scenario, settlers are responding with fear, anger and, in
some cases, threats of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several days, Barak has used his frankest language
yet to describe territorial concessions his government is prepared
to make to achieve a peace agreement. Talks aimed at reaching a
final accord are to resume in the Washington area early next week,
visiting U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of explosive sentiments over West Bank land that many
Jewish settlers consider their biblical birthright, Barak has been
emphasizing what Israel will seek to retain rather than what it is
ready to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the prime minister brings an agreement that puts 150,000
settlers in the West Bank in large settlement blocs ... under
Israeli sovereignty in an agreement recognized by the entire world,
it's a historic achievement,'' Barak said Monday night on Israel's
Channel Two television, the latest in a series of similar public
statements.
</P>
<P>
   To listening settlers, who total 200,000 in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, the message was clear: 50,000 of them could be left out
in the cold. Barak, elected overwhelmingly on a peace platform a
year ago, has always said ''painful choices'' would accompany any
peace agreement, but this marked the first time he had cited
specific numbers of settlers who could expect to be uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   And if his public statements were meant as an opening position
in the peace talks, even more settlers could ultimately be left
with the choice of living under Palestinian rule or abandoning
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister said Israel would seek to retain sovereignty
over settlement blocs in the Jerusalem suburbs, to the city's
south, in the northwestern West Bank and in a corridor linking the
Jordan Valley to the rest of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In isolated, thinly populated settlements like Karme Tsur, near
the West Bank town of Hebron, such criteria would leave little
chance of their inclusion. Home to just 500 people, Karme Tsur is
surrounded by Palestinian villages and cut off from any major
settlement bloc -- a prime target for handover.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be a disaster,'' said Esti Uliel, a 37-year-old
mother of five, sitting at her kitchen table in the pleasant, sunny
home she and her husband recently remodeled. ''We couldn't live
under Palestinian authority.''
</P>
<P>
   She predicted any move to hand over settlements like hers would
spark a groundswell of opposition in Israel, even though relatively
few people are affected.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're good citizens -- we vote, we pay taxes, we are
law-abiding,'' she said. ''What is a democracy for, if not to
protect the rights of its minority? I wouldn't cry just for my
house -- I'd cry for the state of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Uliel, who came to Karme Tsur 14 years ago, when it was only a
few houses carved into a raw patch of hillside, said she and her
neighbors would leave -- reluctantly -- if her settlement was among
those relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   Radical settlers, though, are making fiery pledges to stand and
fight -- in language that raises, for some, the specter of the 1995
assassination of Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin by an
ultranationalist opposed to land concessions to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pleas from mainstream settler groups to refrain from
incitement or threats, the extremists are branding Barak a traitor
to his people.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prime minister of the Jews who can even consider taking
Jews out of their house! It borders on fascism,'' said Yaakov
Haiman, from the northern West Bank settlement of Itamar.
</P>
<P>
   However much Barak's new stance might inflame radical settlers,
he can expect a cool reception from the Palestinians, who insist
that all settlements in the West Bank and Gaza Strip are
illegitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our position on the issue of settlements is clear -- they
should all be dismantled, and any other suggestion is rejected,''
said Nabil Abourdeneh, a senior adviser to Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
