<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Conference Addresses Men  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Thousands of women activists have gathered
to work toward ending gender-based violence, reaching equality
between the sexes and assuring reproductive rights to all. Many,
though, have found that men can't be left out of the process.
</P>
<P>
   The role of men in women's issues is one of the key points that
the United Nations wants to raise in this week's meetings to review
the progress made toward women's equality since the 1995 U.N.
conference of women in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to challenge the boys to understand the issue of
consent, as well as challenging girls to understand that they have
the right to say no,'' Noeleen Heyzer, executive director of the
U.N. Development Fund for Women, said Tuesday at a panel on ''Men
and Boys Preventing Violence Against Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyzer believes that including men in women's issues has become
more pressing since the Beijing conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''After Beijing, we were able to launch all these campaigns and
put them into action. We realized how important it was to include
men,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Development Fund for Women has recently launched
several projects addressing men and boys, including campaigns in
schools and in police stations.
</P>
<P>
   Involving men is necessary because often men will not listen to
women, said Norman Tjombe, who organized a meeting of hundreds of
men in Namibia to discuss violence against women.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting had an effect. ''A week later, we saw a large
demonstration of men wanting to prevent a suspect accused of rape
from getting out on bail,'' Tjombe said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still few men to be seen at the conference, and
actually getting men involved in women's issues may be more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kaufman, international director of the White Ribbon
Campaign, says one way is to launch positive campaigns for men.
Kaufman's Canada-based group urges men to wear a white ribbon as a
''public pledge never to commit violence against women, never to
condone it, and never to remain silent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not an anti-male campaign,'' said Kaufman, adding that
''positive campaigns'' also may stop a backlash from men who feel
excluded from the women's movement. ''It says very clearly to men
that we must be allied to women.''
</P>
<P>
   Another argument to involve men is that improving women's
situation is beneficial to all.
</P>
<P>
   Violence is ''debilitating to both parts of society,'' said Guy
Hewitt of the gender affairs department of the Commonwealth
Secretariat, the administrative body for the 54-nation group of
Britain and its former colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Women have learned from experience to include men in their
battle for equality, said Sreelakshmi Gururaja, senior adviser on
gender and development at UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   ''We found in the 1980s that we could increase the power of
women, but the relationship (between men and women) did not
change,'' Gururaja said. ''If we want transformation, we need
transformation in both men and women.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Development Fund for Women: http://www.unifem.undp.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
