<DOCNO> APW20000607.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Decision Expected on Friday  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- After a meeting with Steve Young, Denver Broncos
coach Mike Shanahan came away with a ''strong feeling of what
(Young) is going to do.'' He's not telling, however.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan on Tuesday refused to be specific about Young's
intentions, saying only that Young will make an announcement,
probably on Friday, about whether he will play for the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Young could also elect to play for the Seattle Seahawks, retire
from the game or even return to the San Francisco 49ers. The latter
option appeared to be ruled out by 49ers general manager Bill
Walsh, but Walsh reversed himself Tuesday, saying Young could stay
if he gets medical clearance.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the 49ers granted Young permission to negotiate a
contract with the Broncos. Shanahan interrupted his charity golf
tournament to meet with Young at a Denver hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The pair had an ''in-depth conversation,'' Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe his mind is made up,'' Shanahan told the media
Tuesday following the first day of his team's four-day minicamp.
''But I'll let Steve share that with you. I think he's going to
have a press conference on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said the meeting with Young, whom he coached in San
Francisco, lasted 90 minutes to two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a great conversation,'' Shanahan said. ''We bounced
some things off of each other. He asked me some questions, and I
asked him some questions. I believe the big question that everybody
has is about his health. I asked a lot of questions relative to
that. He said he felt like he knows more about concussions than
most doctors. He has studied it quite a bit and has taken a lot of
tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, 38, missed the final 13 games of the 1999 season because
of a severe concussion, prompting some friends to urge him to
retire. He has had four concussions in the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers haven't given Young medical clearance to continue
playing, and their attempts to retain Young also are hampered by
salary-cap concerns. Walsh insisted Tuesday that the 49ers do have
cap room to keep Young.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it did work out with the Broncos,'' Shanahan said, ''our
doctors would have to approve him. So there are some question marks
right now. I asked if he was pushing the envelope a little bit to
play. But he feels very good about where he's at relative to his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would not want him to take a chance of playing if the
doctors had any question about it. I want to do the best thing for
Steve and the best thing for our organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, the most accurate passer in NFL history and twice the
league's MVP, said in San Francisco on Tuesday his meeting with
Shanahan was to gather information and that there was no contract
talk or negotiations. Those close to Young said he also wanted to
meet with Seattle coach Mike Holmgren before making any decision
about his NFL future.
</P>
<P>
   ''I spoke with Mike Shanahan based on the fact that he is one of
the guys who was really important in my career,'' Young said.
''Everyone knows how much respect I have for Mike. I sought the
permission specifically so that I could go and not be in trouble
for talking with somebody else who is a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have three options, basically. I could retire, I could play
for San Francisco or I could play somewhere else. I have a big
decision to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said he and Young ''have had a great relationship. I
think the world of him as a person, not only as a football player.
He's a class act, a cinch Hall of Famer.''
</P>
<P>
   And the coach left little doubt that Young could help his team,
which slumped to 6-10 last year under inexperienced quarterback
Brian Griese after back-to-back Super Bowl titles under John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Steve could help any football team at the highest
level,'' he said. ''I like the way he's played over the last few
years. He keeps himself in great shape. He's a student of the game.
He's a great competitor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0118 </TRAILER>
