<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Europe Tour A Last Hurrah  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER R. MEARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- It was a rally to stir the political soul
of any candidate. But none was there. Only Bill Clinton, the
American president, at the finale of his farewell tour of Europe,
in the twilight of his term.
</P>
<P>
   His was the campaigner's wave, the fence-line handshaking, the
cheerleading speech to the throng stretching far down the broad
mall beyond St. Michael's Square on Monday, at the last show of his
week of European conferences including the summit in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   These wouldn't have been his voters anyhow, of course. But when
he stood before them in the blazing evening sun, the old Clinton
seemed revived, the man who pressed every hand in reach, beamed as
he shared the stand with the conductor of the Odessa Symphony
Orchestra, waving in time as they played ''Take Me Out To The
Ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had seemed subdued, almost wistful, at earlier stops,
occasions of state, as though bent on leaving the image of
statesman rather than that of a politician playing to the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   His summit conference with Russian President Vladimir Putin was
cordial enough, by the account of both men, but without the hearty
embraces of his sessions with Boris Yeltsin, retired from office
now as Clinton will be at noon next Jan. 21. He paid what he called
an old-times visit to Yeltsin at his retirement dacha outside
Moscow and said he found his old diplomatic friend happy and
looking good.
</P>
<P>
   So ended his summit weekend in Moscow, after sessions in which
Putin said he found Clinton a comfortable negotiating partner, and
Clinton said it was productive, even to deal with differences
candidly and clearly.
</P>
<P>
   They had those, even as they signed preordained agreements to
eliminate 34 tons apiece of weapons-grade plutonium over the next
20 years and to open a joint missile launch early warning system in
Moscow. They issued a joint statement declaring dedication to arms
control, but with the U.S. aim of building a national missile
defense still in dispute, and with no progress on a third nuclear
arms reduction treaty -- the Senate hasn't yet fully ratified the
second -- in which the Russians want sharper weapons cuts than
Washington will accept.
</P>
<P>
   In Kiev, Clinton and President Leonid Kuchma celebrated with a
champagne toast at the presidential palace Monday as the Ukrainian
leader announced that the last nuclear power plant at Chernobyl,
site of the 1986 disaster, will be shut down on Dec. 15. That, too,
was long in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton showed little fire in his address to the Russian
parliament Monday, a 45-minute speech with some of the elements,
but none of the hearty style of a State of the Union message to
Congress. He offered a series of recommendations to the Duma on
economic reform, down to overhauling the tax code for fairness to
attract foreign investors. This after saying that one problem in
the relationship is an American tendency to press its answers to
problems as though Washington knows everything.
</P>
<P>
   Then to Kiev, and to the ancient square, with one gold-domed
cathedral, blue and white and just rebuilt and rededicated, behind
the yellow-and-blue-decked platform where Clinton spoke. Another,
dating from the 11th century and now being renovated, loomed far
down the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Kiev police estimated 50,000 people were in the crowd in front
of Clinton. They waved small flags, the blue and yellow of Ukraine
and the red, white and blue of the United States, cheered his
summons to build a stronger democracy and a free economy, delivered
with pauses for translation.
</P>
<P>
   Giant American flags were waved across the mall over the crowd
some 300 yards from the platform.
</P>
<P>
   They had come hours earlier, to stand in 86-degree heat, as
Ukrainian rock stars and bands performed as they awaited Clinton.
The Odessa symphony took the train up to Kiev for its part of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had more advice, urging Ukrainians to build free markets
for prosperity beyond the hard times that followed the fall of
communism in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It was a solo. Kuchma, just re-elected president over a
communist rival, stayed at the palace. This was Clinton's show.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do not give up,'' he cried. ''Keep on fighting. Borites,
poboryte.''
</P>
<P>
   His translation of ''Keep on fighting,'' which is close, but not
quite, literal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that beat the unintended translation of one Ukrainian
phrase to English back at the palace. It was fractured into an
observation that the two presidents had signed far-fetched
agreements, instead of the intended far reaching.
</P>
<P>
   Even when there is not a vote to be had, Clinton rises to the
crowds, the campaign instinct surviving his last campaign at home.
He beamed, he waved, he paused at the applause lines. They may have
turned out for the rock stars, but they certainly cheered Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Speech done, he went straight to the fence line for a half-hour
of hand shaking. The band played Bennie Goodman classics. ''Swing,
swing, swing.'' The symphony took its turn. ''The Stars and Stripes
Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   His last election is history, but Clinton has few rivals at
working a crowd. Americans or Ukrainians.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears has reported on Washington and
national politics for The Associated Press for more than 35 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0121 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine Wins N.J. Senate Nomination  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Propelled from obscurity by his
record-shattering $33 million campaign, retired investment banker
Jon Corzine captured New Jersey's Democratic Senate nomination
Tuesday and ruined the comeback hopes of former Gov. Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   With 95 percent of precincts reporting, Corzine led with 239,291
votes, or 58 percent. Florio drew 172,564 votes, or 42 percent.
Corzine outpolled Florio by more than 3-1 in the vote-rich Newark
area, while Florio did well in his base in southern New Jersey near
Camden -- but couldn't overcome Corzine's strength.
</P>
<P>
   ''Make no mistake. I want to invest in America,'' Corzine told
supporters. ''That is what this campaign will be about.''
</P>
<P>
   On the GOP side, Rep. Bob Franks edged out a win in a close
four-way race. And in a repeat of a nail-biter two years ago,
moderate GOP Rep. Marge Roukema, the longest-serving woman in
Congress, narrowly defeated a conservative challenger.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic Senate race was the highlight of primary
voting in six states Tuesday. Corzine has never held elected office
but quickly gained endorsements from top state political leaders,
including the man he hopes to replace, retiring three-term
Democratic Sen. Frank Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, seeking a return to politics after voters dumped him in
1993 at the end of just one term because he raised taxes by $2.8
billion, accused Corzine of trying to buy the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's primary spending, roughly $140 per vote, shattered the
previous U.S. record for a Senate campaign -- $30 million spent by
Republican Michael Huffington in his losing 1994 bid for office in
California.
</P>
<P>
   The former Goldman Sachs chief executive, with a personal
fortune estimated at $400 million, raised $2.5 million for the
campaign. The rest came from his own pocket.
</P>
<P>
   He unleashed a $2-million-per-week blitz of TV commercials and
poured hundreds of thousands of dollars into state and county
Democratic organizations. Florio denounced the tactic as a
''hostile corporate takeover'' of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   After his defeat, Florio said the primary campaign was a
''monument to the need for campaign finance reform.'' But he said
he would support Corzine in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters shrugged off the criticism of Corzine's spending.
Norm Reiff, 69, of Northfield, said he picked Corzine, ''in spite
of all the money he put into it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a new face,'' Reiff said. ''Let's give him a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The attention paid to Corzine's spending and his campaign
platforms, such as federal funding of college for students with B
averages or better and investing Social Security funds in the stock
market, dwarfed interest in the GOP primary for Lautenberg's seat.
</P>
<P>
   After GOP Gov. Christie Whitman said she would not run, four
lesser-known candidates stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   With 98 percent of precincts counted, Franks won with 36 percent
of the vote, pulling ahead of state Sen. William Gormley, who led
in early returns but only drew 34 percent by the end. Trailing were
Essex County Executive Jim Treffinger and Ramapo College professor
Murray Sabrin. The GOP has not won a Senate seat in New Jersey
since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   In a bitter primary fight in New Jersey, Roukema, seeking her
11th term, once again beat back a tough challenge from conservative
state Assemblyman Scott Garrett. Garrett, who came within 1,700
votes of beating Roukema two years ago, lost this time by about
1,500 votes. He received $100,000 worth of support in ads from a
conservative group.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday also marked the end of the presidential primary season,
with contests in five of the six states, though they held little
import since George W. Bush and Al Gore locked up their nominations
back in March. The sixth state, Iowa, held its caucuses in January.
</P>
<P>
   In the other states:
</P>
<P>
   --Alabama Circuit Judge Roy Moore, who fought the American Civil
Liberties Union in 1995 to post the Ten Commandments in his
courtroom, won the GOP nomination for chief justice of the state
Supreme Court. Moore, who bucked Republican leaders to run for the
seat, took 56 percent of the vote in a four-way race and avoided a
run-off.
</P>
<P>
   --In Montana, Democratic farmer Brian Schweitzer made the high
price of prescription medicine the theme of his Senate campaign,
taking buses of seniors to Canada to highlight the price
differences. He easily won the nomination to face two-term GOP Sen.
Conrad Burns in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Montana, state Auditor Mark O'Keefe won the Democratic
nomination to replace Republican Gov. Mark Racicot, forced by term
limits to retire. Lt. Gov. Judy Martz won the GOP race.
</P>
<P>
   And in New Jersey, former GOP Rep. Dick Zimmer, a lawyer who
teaches at Princeton, defeated another former GOP congressman, Mike
Pappas, to challenge first-term Democratic Rep. Rush Holt. Pappas
lost to Holt two years ago in part because of a ditty he sang about
impeachment on the House floor (''Twinkle, Twinkle, Kenneth
Starr'').
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere:
</P>
<P>
   -- In New Mexico, former Rep. Bill Redmond won a three-way GOP
race to challenge three-term Democratic Sen. Jeff Bingaman.
</P>
<P>
   -- In Iowa, lawyer Jay Marcus won the GOP nomination to challenge
two-term Democratic Rep. Leonard Boswell.
</P>
<P>
   -- In the race for South Dakota's lone House seat, Curt Hohn,
manager of a water pipeline, won the Democratic primary to
challenge two-term GOP Rep. John Thune.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
