<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson Eyed As Gore's V.P.  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Richardson flops onto an overstuffed
couch in his office, peels off a shoe and starts rubbing his left
foot.
</P>
<P>
   ''Man, these things are killing me,'' says Richardson, America's
energy secretary and former United Nations ambassador. ''Your feet
swell up when you're on airplanes a lot, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson has been traveling almost nonstop lately -- trying to
get oil-producing countries to boost their output and bring down
gasoline prices, visiting a New Mexico nuclear lab scorched by a
wildfire, stumping for Vice President Al Gore's Democratic
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Now Richardson, 52, is being mentioned as Gore's potential
running mate. Gore aides positioned him right behind the vice
president as Gore claimed victory in the March 7 Super Tuesday
primaries, getting Richardson right in TV-camera view and
increasing the Washington buzz about the top Hispanic in President
Clinton's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson says he would be honored to be on the ticket but is
not openly pursuing the job. Former Secretary of State Warren
Christopher, who is heading Gore's running mate search, met with
Richardson last month in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   His down-to-earth, take-off-your-shoes personality, friends and
supporters say, stands Richardson in good stead, whether he's
trying to win the release of captives from the likes of Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein or wooing skeptical voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's very comfortable in situations that would make you or I
very uncomfortable,'' said Earl Potter, a friend for more than two
decades. ''He's very used to walking into a room and having
everybody with their swords drawn and being very antagonistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson credits his upbringing. Born in California to a
Boston banker father and a Mexican mother, Richardson spent most of
his childhood in Mexico City. He spoke English with his father and
Spanish with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ''The personal background of being bicultural makes resolving
differences between cultures something that appeals to me,''
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats lobbying for Richardson for vice president include
prominent Hispanics such as former California state Assembly
Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa. Backers say having Richardson on the
ticket could help Gore in heavily Latino states like California,
Illinois and even Texas, home to GOP contender and Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never before in this country's history have either of the
major parties nominated a Hispanic candidate. This could be a
historic moment,'' said David Garcia, executive director of the New
Mexico Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson does not want to be defined by his heritage
alone, and says that's one reason he's focused on ''nontraditional,
non-Hispanic'' issues such as diplomacy and trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe you're a stronger Hispanic advocate if you're a
player in the mainstream,'' he said. ''I'm very proud to be
Hispanic. But the key to being successful as an American public
figure is not to be pigeonholed.''
</P>
<P>
   But as energy secretary, Richardson risks being pigeonholed as
the head of an agency that makes news mainly for its missteps. He
took the helm of the agency in 1998, just as controversy surged
about the agency's handling of alleged spying at nuclear weapons
labs.
</P>
<P>
   And although gasoline prices have eased from their highs of
earlier this year, another jump in price could increase criticism
of Richardson -- and hurt his running-mate prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ''I relish solving problems,'' Richardson said. ''I've fired
contractors. I've done international initiatives. I've used
diplomacy to get this department a high profile. But there are
still a lot of problems we have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   As a New Mexico congressman, Richardson alienated some core
Democratic supporters -- labor unions and environmentalists -- with
his strong support for the North American Free Trade Agreement.
Labor opposed NAFTA because of the potential for job losses to
Mexico, while some environmentalists worried the pact could
undermine U.S. environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   An advantage is Richardson's diplomatic experience. While in
Congress, he negotiated the release of American captives held by
North Korea, Iraq and Sudanese rebels. Clinton named him ambassador
to the United Nations in 1997, where he worked to negotiate peace
among warring factions in Afghanistan and central Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Picking Richardson also could help Gore win New Mexico, a state
regarded as a toss-up in the presidential race. New Mexico has only
five electoral votes, but friends and supporters say he would be a
relentless campaigner who could connect with voters who have been
turned off by politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has a take-charge attitude, a dogged pursuit of any goal he
sets,'' said Jeff Smith, a friend from high school who later served
as chief of staff in Richardson's congressional office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0133 </TRAILER>
