<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deposits, Heart Disease Linked  </HEADLINE>
By LINDSEY TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Heart disease -- America's No. 1 killer -- could be
reduced by the development of drugs to prevent calcium deposits in
arteries of the heart, suggests a study published today.
</P>
<P>
   The deposits are thought to be precursors to the fatty buildups
that cause a narrowing of the arteries and lead to heart attacks
and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   People with calcium deposits are much more likely to be smokers
and have high blood pressure and high cholesterol levels. All of
those factors are thought to contribute to calcification.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're seeing here is a consequence of lifestyle that is
modifiable, so we're looking at a condition that is preventable,''
said Dr. Carlos Iribarren, a researcher at the Kaiser Permanente
Medical Care Program in Oakland, Calif., who led the study.
</P>
<P>
   Because calcium deposits do not automatically lead to heart
disease in all cases, Iribarren said it is too soon to recommend
widespread screening. Such screening could, in turn, lead to more
invasive tests.
</P>
<P>
   The study of 116,309 men and women in a San Francisco-area
Kaiser health maintenance program was published in today's Journal
of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The participants were ages 30 to 89 and had not been diagnosed
with heart disease when they were given chest X-rays during a
checkup between 1964 and 1973. Their medical records were obtained
for the ensuing years.
</P>
<P>
   Those whose X-rays showed calcium deposits ran a 25 percent
higher risk of developing heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Women with the deposits faced a 50 percent higher risk of having
blood clot-related strokes. Among men, there was no increased
stroke risk.
</P>
<P>
   While previous studies have shown that calcification is a risk
factor for heart disease, the researchers said their findings
clarify the extent of the risk.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar study published in 1996, calcium deposits were
discovered through an ultrafast type of CT scanning called Electron
Beam Computed Tomography.
</P>
<P>
   EBCT is better at detecting the deposits than traditional X-rays
but was not available at the start of Iribarren's research.
Iribarren said his study thus may not have identified the full
extent of the risk.
</P>
<P>
   EBCT is also expensive -- about $400 to $500 a scan.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://jama.ama-assn.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Menigitis Vaccine Tested in Babies  </HEADLINE>
By TAMMY WEBBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A new vaccine is the first to safely and
effectively immunize infants against a form of meningococcal
disease, a leading cause of bacterial meningitis, researchers
reported today in the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   British researchers tested the meningococcal C vaccine on 182
infants in Oxfordshire, England, and found it gave them
long-lasting antibodies against the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Although Britain began routinely using the vaccine in infants at
the end of 1999, it is not yet available in the United States,
where approval could take two to three years, said Nancy
Rosenstein, an epidemiologist at the Centers of Disease Control and
Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Meningococcal C bacteria cause about one-third of the 3,000 U.S.
cases of meningococcal disease each year; types Y and B cause the
others. There are no vaccines against Y and B for infants.
</P>
<P>
   Meningococcal disease can cause bacterial meningitis, an
infection of the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord. The
disease can also cause a fatal bloodstream infection.
</P>
<P>
   A meningococcal vaccine now used in the United States is not
recommended for infants, whose immune systems are not fully
developed. It also eventually stops protecting. It is most often
used to treat outbreaks of the disease and to inoculate travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government has approved two other infant vaccines to
prevent diseases that can cause meningitis -- one is effective
against the Haemophilus influenzae type b, the other against
pneumococcal bacteria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Head Seeks U.S. Funds  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE E. ERBSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Argentina's president embarks on
his first official visit to the United States this weekend in
search of new investments and lower trade barriers, conceding his
economy may grow slower than expected this year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday with The Associated Press, Fernando De
la Rua also defended austerity policies that have caused some
discontent among citizens paying higher taxes, public workers with
reduced salaries and hard-line unions disgruntled by labor reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina, Latin America's third-largest economy, has struggled
to recover from a 22-month recession brought on by the 1997 Asian
financial crisis, and compounded by Brazil's devaluation of its
currency.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th-century Pink House, the downtown presidential office
building, De la Rua said his economic advisers have scaled back
Argentina's growth target for the year from 4 percent to 3.5
percent, ''or maybe a little less.''
</P>
<P>
   But many private economists say the country will come out of the
recession with an expansion rate of 2.5 percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua's first U.S. visit since assuming the presidency six
months ago comes amid national belt-tightening. The 62-year-old
president is to meet financial and business leaders in New York on
Monday and President Clinton on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will be seeking increased private investment from
American firms, especially in telecommunications, and will be
pressing the Clinton administration to reduce import restrictions
on Argentine goods such as steel pipe, orange juice and beef.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua announced a new round of spending cuts in late May as
he tries to re-ignite the idling economy. His plan calls for an
annual 12 percent to 15 percent reduction in the salaries of state
employees, a deregulation of the country's health system and a cut
in state pensions, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, De la Rua said government deficits ''have been
reduced'' and his administration is ''taking hard measures firmly
for the country's economic health.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua stressed that while he has tried to wring savings out
of the budget, he hasn't cut spending on public health and
education, ''we have increased efficiency, but have made no cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions and civil servants have protested the measures,
including a national work stoppage Friday. But De la Rua said he
does not view it ''as an expression of a permanent social crisis,''
nor as a forerunner of social violence.
</P>
<P>
   A bulletin board along a corridor near the president's office
was festooned with leaflets urging a staff walkout Friday. As
reporters crossed a patio leading to the presidential wing, a
shower of leaflets in support of the stoppage fluttered down from
an upper balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment stands at 14 percent and many companies have taken
jobs across the border to Brazil, which devalued its currency in
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's exports are more expensive and thus less competitive
because of the one-for-one link of the Argentine peso to the
dollar. But De la Rua said he would not consider eliminating it.
''Maintaining parity is necessary'' to protect the country's
economic infrastructure, he said. Much local debt is denominated in
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua also reaffirmed Argentina's support for the
four-nation trading bloc known as Mercosur, which also includes
neighboring Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay. He predicted the group
would have a common currency ''within two or three years,''
although financial experts have predicted it would take at least 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua also said the Mercosur countries as a group support
Clinton's call for a hemisphere-wide free trade area, even though
some of them have shown no great enthusiasm for the idea.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua held to the traditional Latin American posture of
nonintervention when asked for his reaction to the May 28 run-off
election in Peru, boycotted by opposition candidate Alejandro
Toledo and won by incumbent President Alberto Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   He questioned the electoral process, but said economic sanctions
against Peru, proposed by some critics, would cause hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people would suffer,'' he said. ''I am against
blockades.''
</P>
<P>
   The usually reserved De la Rua became emotional while discussing
a planned visit to the Holocaust Memorial in Washington, and said
he had recently hosted a reception honoring Holocaust survivors at
the Pink House.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked for their forgiveness,'' he said, speaking of
Argentina's role in harboring Nazi war criminals after World War
II, and for the difficulties imposed on refugees seeking to enter
the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0147 </TRAILER>
