<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. Gov. Backs Income Tax  </HEADLINE>
By TOM SHARP
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Gov. Don Sundquist views an income tax
as the way to Tennessee's financial salvation, but the roadblocks
are mounting.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Republican proposed a 3.75 percent personal income
tax, his own party has deserted him, lawmakers are backing away
from him and he is booed in public. A columnist for the
conservative National Review magazine even dubbed him the worst
governor in America.
</P>
<P>
   Sundquist is sticking to his guns. He believes the tax will save
Tennessee -- routinely at the bottom of national rankings for
spending on education, health care and law enforcement -- from
becoming ''a second-rate state.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The collapse of our tax structure occurred on my watch,'' he
said. ''I could patch this thing up for another year or two and let
somebody else worry about it, but I didn't run for office to get
by, to do what was politically expedient.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is one of nine states without a general personal
income tax. It is facing a budget shortfall of roughly $300 million
when the nation's economy is at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   Sundquist has proposed the income tax to fund an $18.2 billion
budget for the next fiscal year. His plan would decrease a 6
percent state sales tax to 3.75 percent on most goods and eliminate
it from food. It also would revoke a tax on certain interest and
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature has rejected several business tax proposals and
the income tax during the past 15 months, instead looking at
alternatives such as raising taxes on liquor, wine, beer,
cigarettes and home heating energy, or possibly using money from
the national tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Sundquist has threatened to veto any budget that doesn't include
tax reform and to call a third special session this summer, when 99
House members and 16 of 33 Senate members plan to be home
campaigning for re-election in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is war,'' declared Tommy Hopper, a former state GOP
chairman and a leading anti-income tax activist. ''It will not shed
blood but it will destroy careers. It will tear apart (political)
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters have voiced their opposition to the tax plan in
horn-honking protests and letters to the editor.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail sent this week to House members, postal service
worker Lynn Gabriel of Hermitage asked: ''Why can't there be cuts
instead of tax increases? If we can't live off a 7 percent increase
a year in income, there is a definite problem with someone spending
way too much money.''
</P>
<P>
   About 56 cents of every state tax dollar comes from the 6
percent sales tax, but some pay as much as 8.75 percent because of
local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Tennesseans cross the line to shop in eight
surrounding states with income taxes and lower sales taxes. Many
also are lured by lotteries, which are illegal in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the out-of-state workers who commute to
Tennessee, never paying taxes where they use roads and other
services.
</P>
<P>
   ''I go to these national governor's meetings and I'm jealous and
embarrassed,'' Sundquist said. ''I have to listen to all these
states with huge surpluses trying to figure out how to cut their
taxes, and here we are at the bottom without a way to collect from
people who ought to be paying.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only last year, however, that Sundquist began to embrace
an income tax as the solution. He opposed it for most of his
political career -- six terms as a congressman and his first term as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   But when a decline in business taxes forced a reassessment of
the tax system, Sundquist said he found it unfair and regressive.
After lawmakers rejected three business tax plans, he forged ahead
with the income tax proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to tell the people of Tennessee I made a mistake,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sundquist says that while the income tax would raise $450
million more for the state coffers, residents would pay $54 million
less in taxes under his plan. He said he is disappointed by the
public opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The lone outspoken supporter of Sundquist's plan is state Sen.
Bob Rochelle, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public has been told for so long that no politician acts
in the general best interest that it's taken them a long time to
understand that's what we're trying to do,'' Rochelle said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Sundquist was booed when introduced at a celebration
of the Tennessee Titans' American Football Conference championship.
Anti-tax groups have run radio and television ads across the state,
and organized protests at the capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Republican Party voted in December not to support
his plan. Legislators who might have agreed with the governor were
scared off by the public's outcry.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you see zero support for an issue it's just a futile
waste of time to continue to pursue it,'' said House Republican
Leader Steve McDaniel.
</P>
<P>
   The 64-year-old Sundquist ends his second term as governor in
2002 and doesn't plan to seek another political office. If he ends
his career as the hated governor who supported an income tax, so be
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm confident that what I'm doing will be vindicated in the
future, that people will look back and say, 'He made the decisions
that should have been made, he led the way he should have led, and
what he said was accurate.'''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Legislature: www.legislature.state.tn.us
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee government: www.state.tn.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
