<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore To Appear in DNC Ad  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ads featuring Al Gore and the issue of
prescription drugs for senior citizens will hit TV airwaves in more
than a dozen states on Thursday as the Democratic National
Committee launches a multimillion-dollar campaign to boost its
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The ads will feature Gore discussing drug coverage and will
outline differences in how the two political parties approach the
issue, two senior Democrats said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drugs are not covered under Medicare. The Clinton
administration has proposed a plan for drug coverage, but
congressional Republicans have been slow to embrace the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, which will be identical across the country, will air in
15 states including much of the Midwest battleground, according to
several Democratic officials, speaking on condition of anonymity. A
Spanish version will air on Hispanic stations, one top Democrat
said.
</P>
<P>
   This first ad will continue at least through Sunday, the start
of a campaign that will cost upward of $25 million and continue
through the Democratic National Convention in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign, which has worked closely with the DNC in
developing the ads, has little money left from a hard-fought
primary to air commercials of its own. Therefore, the vice
president is relying on the party to carry his message until the
campaign's coffers are restocked after he becomes the official
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The ads dovetail with plans being developed to have the
Democratic presidential candidate crisscross battleground states
next week, in what some Gore aides described as a ''prosperity
tour'' highlighting the Clinton-Gore administration's economic
record.
</P>
<P>
   The ads comes as Gore shifts his campaign into a positive mode,
setting aside direct attacks on Republican rival George W. Bush.
Like Gore on the stump, the summer ad campaign will include upbeat
messages about his life story and Democratic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Some recent national polls suggest Gore's new approach may be
working, although Bush has led Gore in many surveys and, at this
early stage, the Texas governor is performing better in the
state-by-state contest.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC ad campaign has been anticipated for months and was
expected to start soon after Gore and Bush wrapped up the party
nominations in March.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gore challenged Republicans to forgo ads paid for with
unlimited contributions known as soft money, promising that the DNC
wouldn't run these ads ''unless and until'' the Republican National
Committee did.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans now charge that Gore is breaking his pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ''It sounds like to me they're laying out a smoke screen to
provide an excuse for Al Gore to break his promise,'' Bush said
Tuesday in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats respond that the proposal was never accepted and note
that the original challenge included Republican-leaning outside
groups, which have already spent more than $2 million in anti-Gore
ads.
</P>
<P>
   ''They rejected my offer,'' Gore said Tuesday on ABC's ''Good
Morning America.'' The pro-Bush ads, he said, began airing ''months
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are likely to respond with an ad campaign of their
own, and they have more money available.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC is targeting a half dozen states in the traditional
battleground stretching from Pennsylvania across the Midwest,
including Ohio, Michigan, Illinois, Missouri and Wisconsin, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   It also will air the spots in states where they should hold the
edge and in others that lean Republican, where Gore hopes to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   The ads will air in three states -- Iowa, Oregon and Washington --
that have voted Democratic in the last three elections. Gore
advisers say they are confident he will win those states and hope
that buying ad time there will tempt Bush to spend -- and waste --
money in states he will ultimately lose.
</P>
<P>
   The ads will also run in several Southern states -- Florida,
Georgia, Louisiana and Kentucky, as Gore pushes into territory
where President Clinton did well. They're also set for Maryland,
aimed at viewers in neighboring Delaware, a swing state, and in New
Mexico, another tight race.
</P>
<P>
   In total, according to a tally by the Bush campaign, the DNC is
spending about $1.9 million on this weekend of advertising, buying
most major markets in each state. An AP survey found the DNC buying
ad time in Seattle, St. Louis and Tampa, Fla., and across the state
of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: AP Political Writer Ron Fournier contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
