<HEADLINE> Taiwan Gets OK To Test Missiles  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan has obtained permission from the
United States to test the U.S.-built Patriot missiles in the
island, the first time the missiles will be tested outside the
United States, defense officials said today.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, designed to intercept incoming missiles, are an
important part of Taiwan's defense against China's Dongfeng-31 -- a
nuclear-capable missile that can reach as far as the western United
States.
</P>
<P>
   A military spokesman who spoke on customary anonymity said
Taiwan received permission to test the PAC-2 next year, and only
have to work out the details. He did not say when the United States
had given its permission.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's military has acquired 200 PAC-2 missiles, upgraded
versions of the Patriots used by U.S. forces during the 1991
Persian Gulf War. Taiwan has test-fired the missiles in the United
States, but the military wants to observe how they work in Taiwan's
subtropical climate.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's defense chief Wu Shih-wen last week confirmed Taiwan's
wanted to test the Patriot missiles outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   China will test-fire its Dongfeng-31 missiles in the near
future, Chinese-language newspapers reported today, without
specifying when the tests would be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   It would be China's fifth test of the missile, and the flight
path would likely be from the northern Shanxi region toward China's
northwestern Xinjiang region, the respected China Times quoted
Taiwanese security officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwanese defense officials said they had no information on the
reports.
</P>
<P>
   China and Taiwan split amid civil war in 1949. Although the two
sides have been ruled separately for decades, Beijing views Taiwan
as a breakaway province that must be reunited with the mainland, by
force if necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0225 </TRAILER>
