<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bipartisan Patients' Rights Possible  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats said they may bypass House-Senate
negotiations on a patients' bill of rights and introduce as early
as today a bipartisan bill on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The move is being led by Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., a key
member of the committee that has been working for more than three
months to combine bills passed by the House and Senate aimed at
strengthening the hand of patients in dealing with HMOs and other
health plans.
</P>
<P>
   With talks stalled and time running out before the summer
recess, Kennedy and other Democrats are ready to take alternative
steps to get a bill, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   As early as today, Kennedy may offer legislation -- fashioned
after the bipartisan House bill favored by the White House and some
Republicans -- as an amendment to a defense authorization bill now
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The new bill would guarantee basic protections for all 161
million Americans in private health plans, establish a process for
appealing HMO decisions and expand patients' rights to sue their
health plans if they were harmed by decisions not to cover care.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans cast doubt on whether the bill could pass
and accused Democrats of trying to foil efforts to reach bipartisan
agreement so they could tell voters this fall that Republicans
wouldn't support patient protections.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and his allies believe re-election pressures will bring
enough GOP support, because some senators will want their campaigns
to address patients' frustrations with managed care organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are optimistic we can do so,'' said Jim Manley, Kennedy's
spokesman. A vote on the defense bill could come within two weeks,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., who is working with
Kennedy on the bill and helping to recruit Senate Republicans, is
looking at including GOP-favored tax provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Possibilities include tax deductions for people who purchase
their own insurance and modest expansion of a medical savings
account pilot program that lets self-employed people save tax-free
money to pay doctor bills, said John Stone, Norwood's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans criticized the Democrats' plan to
circumvent their own efforts to reach a compromise, which would go
to both houses of Congress for a vote and then to President Clinton
for signing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Moving to the floor right now would be an act of extremely
poor faith,'' said Gayle Osterberg, speaking for Sen. Don Nickles,
R-Okla., committee chairman. ''If we are going to have a bipartisan
agreement then folks should be supportive of the conference and
have some patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is still open to a committee agreement on a bill, Manley
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a GOP-backed patients' rights bill last year
that would provide many of the same protections as the proposed
legislation, but would not expand lawsuit rights and applies to
fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   Another patients' rights bill passed last fall would have to be
reintroduced and voted on again in the House, where Republicans are
divided on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Some, siding with Democrats, say all Americans should get
federal protections and health plans should be held liable for
negligence.
</P>
<P>
   Many Senate Republicans, however, believe patient protections
should be left up to states and contend that employers will drop
worker health benefits rather than face expensive lawsuits, adding
to the 44 million uninsured Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0308 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0040 </DOCNO>
