<HEADLINE> Hospital budget predicts surplus at end of next fiscal year  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FARMINGTON, Conn. (AP) - A budget for the next fiscal year at
the University of Connecticut Health Center predicts a $170,000
surplus, the result of an infusion of millions of dollars in state
bailout money.
</P>
<P>
   The $430 million spending package unveiled Tuesday for the
fiscal year that begins July 1 and ends June 30, 2001, includes
$4.4 million in state money, part of $20 million for the health
center approved by the General Assembly in May.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the state money was used to help fill the $21
million hole in this year's budget and to pay for an expansion of
biomedical research.
</P>
<P>
   ''The message to the staff is not to breathe a large sigh of
relief; there are state dollars in this (budget) that are not
recurring,'' said Daniel Upton, interim chief financial officer at
the Farmington health center.
</P>
<P>
   The health center includes UConn's medical and dental schools
and John Dempsey Hospital, which has been losing about $1 million a
month.
</P>
<P>
   UConn officials have said the shortfall is largely the result of
growing discounts in managed care insurance payments, shorter
hospital stays, and a sharp reduction in federal Medicare payments
to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The university has taken several cost-cutting steps, including
an administrative reorganization and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Next year's budget projects a modest increase in the number of
patients treated at John Dempsey and in private doctors' offices at
the center. It also assumes that private grant funding for research
will increase by 17.6 percent to $62.5 million in the next fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   The budget includes $3 million for new programs. Millions more
for those initiatives - including a request for additional state
money - is expected to be included in the health center's 2002 and
2003 budgets. Health center administrators are scheduled to present
plans for those budgets to the board of trustees this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 budget ''is a foundation for the strategic plan,'' said
Lorraine Aronson, UConn's vice president for finance, planning and
management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
