<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 03:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freeh, Reno Clash Over Fund Raising  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying he was ''surprised'' by a comment
linking ''pressure'' in the campaign fund-raising probe to Attorney
General Janet Reno's future in the Clinton administration, FBI
Deputy Director William Esposito immediately informed his boss,
Louis Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   The November 1996 conversation between Esposito and Lee Radek,
chief of the Justice Department public integrity section,
foreshadowed the bitter disagreement between the FBI and top Reno
aides over the handling of the fund-raising investigation. The FBI
said the Justice Department should turn it over to an independent
counsel. The department refused.
</P>
<P>
   Esposito and Radek testified at two congressional hearings
Tuesday as the House Government Reform Committee spewed out 61
Justice Department and FBI documents laying bare the bureaucratic
battle that began in 1996 and continues today.
</P>
<P>
   In one memo, Freeh said he told Reno that Radek's comment about
''pressure'' and Reno's job ''would be enough for me to take him
and the Criminal Division off the case completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying to the Senate Judiciary subcommittee on
administrative oversight and the courts, Esposito recalled being
told by Freeh that Radek's comment ''was a very serious matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Radek flatly denied ever linking Reno's job with the
fund-raising probe. The public integrity chief testified that the
only ''pressure'' he felt was ''to do a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeh's memos were just one of the sources urging Reno to
unleash an independent counsel investigation on President Clinton,
Vice President Al Gore and top administration aides.
</P>
<P>
   While some in the Justice Department said no independent counsel
was warranted, top Reno adviser Bob Litt said an independent
counsel should be appointed to look into possible false statements
by Gore about his fund-raising phone calls from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Radek didn't want an independent counsel for Clinton and Gore.
But Radek did recommend at one point an independent counsel be
appointed to investigate deputy White House chief of staff Harold
Ickes for possibly lying to Congress. Radek was overruled.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Freeh and Justice Department prosecutor Charles
LaBella, head of the Justice Department fund-raising task force,
who were the most vehement. Freeh recounted a Dec. 4, 1998 meeting
with Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ... argued once again that the Attorney General has and had
had for some time an irrevocable political conflict of interest
which makes it inappropriate and -- in my judgment -- impossible for
her ... to make legal ... decisions'' regarding a probe of
President Clinton and Gore, Freeh wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the gravity of the Attorney General's political conflict
of interest -- as well as the DOJ's and her principal advisers -- I
cannot imagine a more compelling matter for the appointment of an
Independent Counsel,'' Freeh concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Radek and the public integrity section that he heads came in for
harsh criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Public Integrity is ... a black hole'' and Radek's nickname is
''Doctor No'' because he always declines to prosecute, complained
Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Public Integrity Section deputy Joseph Gangloff defended Radek
at the hearing before a Senate Judiciary subcommittee, saying the
FBI did not understand some of the complicated legal issues that
needed to be considered when dealing with the law on appointing
independent counsels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 0339 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0042 </DOCNO>
