<HEADLINE> Dow Up 9; Nasdaq Up 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks crept higher in early trading today as
investors awaited word on Microsoft's antitrust case and further
clues on the Federal Reserve's future course on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 9.05 at 10,744.62.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 3.26 at 1,461.10, and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 3.09 at 3,759.46.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft slipped 81.25 cents to $68.813. The judge overseeing
the Microsoft Corp. antitrust case said he would rule today in the
historic case that could lead to a breakup of the software giant.
Microsoft has previously said it will appeal any order to break it
up.
</P>
<P>
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines rose $2.125 to $28.625. KLM and British
Airways confirmed that they have begun talks that could lead to a
merger. An alliance would create the world's third-largest airline,
behind United Airlines and American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways fell $1.313 to $58.25.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, trading was quiet. Analysts said interest rate
worries, which eased last week amid a slew of reports that signaled
a modest economic slowdown, haven't truly left the market. Many
investors are back on the sidelines, waiting for more information
as they try to discern whether the Fed may finally be finished
raising interest rates to cool the pace of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The next crucial piece of data will be the Producer Price Index,
due out Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slender margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 103.61 million
shares, behind Tuesday's moderate pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.44 to 511.21.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 2.1 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.9 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
