<HEADLINE> Jury sequestered after eight hours of deliberations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOCKPORT, N.Y. (AP) - A jury resumed deliberations today in the
case of a man accused of killing a co-worker's husband at her
request.
</P>
<P>
   The Niagara County jury failed to reach a verdict in the
second-degree murder trial of Michael Northrup after eight hours of
deliberations Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Northrup of Caledonia in Livingston County is accused of
shooting John Montstream in June 1998 and leaving the body in the
victim's minivan in a Niagara Falls parking ramp, where it was
found a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Montstream's 41-year-old wife, Annette, is awaiting sentencing
after admitting soliciting someone to kill her husband. She pleaded
guilty in March to first-degree manslaughter and testified that
Northrup, with whom she was romantically involved, volunteered to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Northrup shot Montstream in the town of Sweden
and drove the victim's van to Niagara Falls. He then allegedly
drove home in a pickup truck that he and Annette Montstream had
left there three days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said DNA evidence from Northrup's gun matched that
of John Montstream.
</P>
<P>
   ''This case is about how Annette Montstream and Michael Northrup
planned and carried out the murder of John Montstream, a
37-year-old man and father of two, whose only crime was being
married to Annette Montstream,'' said prosecutor Timothy Lundquist
during a 90-minute closing argument Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Attorney John Parrinello on Monday emphasized the
untrustworthiness of Annette Montstream, who had several sexual
affairs during her marriage and lied to keep from being found out.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Montstream and Northrup had met at a shopping mall where
she worked in a coffee shop and he was a security guard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
