<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paris on Display in Four Shows  </HEADLINE>
By MARILYN AUGUST
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Images of Paris, glorious and grim, are in the
limelight this spring, as four major art shows in the French
capital spotlight the City of Light, past and present.
</P>
<P>
   In black-and white photographs shot mainly at night, Brassai's
Paris, on show at the Georges Pompidou Center through June 26,
chronicles ordinary people in ordinary urban settings.
</P>
<P>
   Prostitutes in seedy hotels bathe in between customers, lovers
embrace in empty subway halls and hobos sleep under bridges over
the Seine.
</P>
<P>
   A master of atmosphere, light and shadow, the Hungarian-born
Brassai, who died in 1954, turned his lens on well-known Paris
monuments. His mist-shrouded statues and glistening cobblestone
boulevards create a certain nocturnal magic all their own.
</P>
<P>
   Also on display are photographs of Paris stone facades. Some are
carved up or defaced so badly that they resemble primitive art.
Others are so cracked and peeling, they border on the best -- or
worst -- of contemporary abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   With sculpture, a tapestry and even a documentary on animals he
filmed at a Paris zoo, the show is one of the most exhaustive ever
mounted of Brassai's work.
</P>
<P>
   Paris becomes the stage for a bloody revolution in two
exhibitions now showing at the Orsay Museum about the Paris revolt
of 1871 -- a milestone in French history long ignored by the art
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   The shows bring together paintings, drawings and photographs
depicting the violence of the period as republican Parisians,
fearing the return of the monarchy, formed a revolutionary
government. The revolt failed, thousands died and bodies littered
the streets of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Grim photographs of executed partisans lined up in their coffins
date from the period. Edouard Manet's drawing, ''Guerre Civile''
(''Civil War''), shows a cadaver sprawled behind the barricades.
</P>
<P>
   Also on display at Orsay is a small show through July 16 devoted
to one of the brightest figures of 19th-century Parisian literary
society -- the dark-haired, creamy-complexioned Nina de Callias.
</P>
<P>
   De Callias was the mystery damsel in Manet's famed ''Dame aux
Eventails'' (''Woman With a Fan''). The painting -- with De Callias
gazing bemusedly at the viewer -- was one of Manet's favorites. He
kept it in his studio and it was not shown until after he died in
1883.
</P>
<P>
   The well-born, free-spirited De Callias flouted social
convention. An accomplished musician and poet, she threw open the
doors of her luxury Paris apartment to the leading avant-garde
figures of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But she fell into disfavor with authorities after harboring
Republican Communards of the 1871 revolt and was forced into exile.
She returned to Paris two years later, but late-night carousing
took a toll on her increasingly fragile mental state, and she died
in 1884, the year Manet's painting of her was shown in public. She
was 41.
</P>
<P>
   On a happier note, the finer things of life designed to decorate
cozy interiors for France's burgeoning bourgeoisie a century ago
are on show at a blockbuster exhibition at the Grand Palais, itself
a stunning example of turn-of-the-century Belle Epoque French
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Entitled ''1900,'' the show is an eclectic overview of
masterpieces executed between 1895 and 1905 and brings together the
best of what artists around the world were doing as the new century
dawned.
</P>
<P>
   A mother-of-pearl hairpin encrusted with diamonds and rubies,
photographs of American Indians dancing during an eclipse of the
moon, and small sculpted heads by Degas, Rodin and Picasso, among
them.
</P>
<P>
   Art Nouveau takes center stage, with dozens of objects
illustrating the trend that saw plants and animals incorporated
into designs of chairs, tables, lamps, flatware and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights: Louis Majorelle's mahogany side table
shaped like a water lily and adorned with chiseled flowers in
gilded bronze, a hairpin encrusted with opals by Rene Lalique, an
ornate silver vegetable dish with mythological figures as handles.
</P>
<P>
   The show runs through June 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 1222 </TRAILER>
