<DOCNO> APW20000607.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Artists Reach Center Stage  </HEADLINE>
By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- For the first time, sound artists have reached
center stage in London.
</P>
<P>
   Works by 26 artists are humming, clicking, whirring, whistling
and banging away in the Hayward Gallery's ''Sonic Boom: The Art of
Sound,'' providing an alternative to art lovers used to looking at
drawings, paintings and sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   One exhibit consists of 51 record players stacked on scaffolding
from floor to ceiling and another is a ''Quiet Club.''
</P>
<P>
   There are dark rooms, flashing lights, sensors in floors to
trigger noise as people pass by, and even bird calls from the
Brazilian rain forest to listen to through headphones while
standing outside looking across the river Thames toward Big Ben.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sonic Boom'' features artists from 10 countries and four
continents, and was put together by David Toop, a British musician,
writer and sound curator.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been involved in this since the 1960s, but even I was
surprised at the amount of work being done when I began moving
around to find people,'' Toop says. ''The sound community is very
big. I could have done 10 different shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the show first see a film called ''The Shaman Girl's
Prayer'' in which Mariko Mori, a Japanese woman who lives in New
York City, appears to be in a kind of trance while manipulating a
white glass ball. Soothing sound surrounds the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Around a corner, a mass of metal and wires coalesces to form a
robot named Yoyo Berimbau, which bangs a drum and plays a string.
It's a creation of Chico MacMurtrie of San Francisco, whose
mechanical sculptures grew out of his art and electronic music
studies at the University of Arizona in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   MacMurtrie has made more than 100 such machines to explore the
''dynamism of sound, movement and form,'' the exhibition catalog
notes.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Extended Schwitters'' of American-born Stephan von Heune,
a German resident, is a plywood figure resembling a semaphore. It
moves and claps and emits nonsense phrases in the style of the
German artist Kurt Schwitters who, between the two world wars, made
art from things thrown away.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Eno, a British musician who specialized in sonic
manipulation by juggling tapes, contributes a sound and light
installation he describes as musical painting. He doesn't work out
the patterns in advance, but uses multiple reproduction systems
that continually and without repetition create ''pictures'' on the
wall of a darkened room -- his ''Quiet Club.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the kind of club I'd like to go to -- Music for More
Senses,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Heri Dono from Yogyakarta, Indonesia, has a line of identical
wooden animal masks on a wall playing a ritualized, repetitive
rhythm which he says are inspired by Javanese Gamelan instruments
and shadow puppetry.
</P>
<P>
   Toop says the Japanese are perhaps the most advanced in sound
art appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Japanese have a sensitivity to sound and they are
interested in newness, in new technology,'' he says. ''They are
aware of precision and delicacy so that off a noisy Kyoto street
you'll find a Zen garden of perfect peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiona Bradley, the Hayward's exhibitions curator, notes that the
art of sound is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ancient Greeks knew about it,'' Bradley says. ''They were
such masters of building open-air theaters in which the actors
could be heard from every seat that it's still a mystery how they
did it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''More and more people are using sound as primary in their
work,'' she says. ''Electronics development has a lot to do with
it, and the rise of video and film technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ferleger Brades, the New Yorker who directs the Hayward,
calls sound ''an integral part of our experience of the world, one
of the tools we use to make sense of our experience. Sound art
manipulates our sense of sound to enlarge the possibilities of that
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Sonic Boom'' is at the Hayward through June 18 and will not
travel. The $24 catalog includes two compact discs containing
nearly two hours of tracks of the artists' work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 1222 </TRAILER>
