<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of June
11-17:
<TEXT>
<P>
   65 years ago: ''Becky Sharp,'' the first full-Technicolor
(three-color) feature, opened at Radio City Music Hall in New York
City. It starred Miriam Hopkins, Billie Burke and Nigel Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   40 years ago: Anthony Perkins and Janet Leigh starred in Alfred
Hitchcock's ''Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   And Billy Wilder's ''The Apartment'' starred Jack Lemmon and
Shirley MacLaine.
</P>
<P>
   35 years ago: The Beatles were each awarded the MBE, or Member
of the British Empire. Some medal holders were so upset, they
returned their medals.
</P>
<P>
   And ''Those Magnificent Men in Their Flying Machines'' starred
Stuart Whitman, Sarah Miles and James Fox.
</P>
<P>
   30 years ago: ''The Long and Winding Road'' by the Beatles
topped the U.S. singles chart.
</P>
<P>
   25 years ago: Karen Black, Henry Gibson, Keith Carradine and
Lily Tomlin were among the stars of Robert Altman's ''Nashville.''
The film had 24 main characters, who improvised at times as they
moved through the worlds of country music and Southern politics.
</P>
<P>
   And Gene Hackman and Jennifer Warren starred in Arthur Penn's
''Night Moves.''
</P>
<P>
   20 years ago: John Travolta and Debra Winger starred in ''Urban
Cowboy.'' The film sparked a fad of mechanical bull riding in bars
across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: ''Dick Tracy'' opened in theaters across the
country. The film starred Warren Beatty, Al Pacino, Madonna, Dustin
Hoffman and James Caan.
</P>
<P>
   And Cher returned to the Las Vegas stage after an eight-year
absence, giving a pop-metal review to a sold-out crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: Madonna's 1969 white Mercedes convertible sold
for $56,350 at an auction of rock 'n' roll memorabilia in New York
City. Bob Dylan's handwritten lyrics to ''Blowin' in the Wind''
drew $8,625, nearly four times the pre-sale estimate, the auction
house said.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: ''Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' took in
$54.9 million on its opening weekend, making more in its first
three days than the original movie did in its entire run. The
original, ''Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery,'' tested
poorly and opened to a tepid $9.5 million in May 1997. But
audiences warmed up to Austin's humor, and the $16 million-budget
film hung on through the summer to gross $53.9 million and turn a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   And the top 10 of The Hollywood Reporter's Star Power '99 survey
of bankable stars were, in order: Tom Hanks, Mel Gibson, Tom
Cruise, Harrison Ford, Jim Carrey, Leonardo DiCaprio, John
Travolta, Julia Roberts, Robin Williams and Brad Pitt. The
Hollywood Reporter surveyed 135 entertainment industry executives,
bankers, buyers and sales agents. The top 10 list was ''a
subjective look at the bankability of 525 actors and actresses
worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken five years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''I do it to get a free seat.'' -- Bill Cosby, explaining why he
had hosted the Playboy Jazz Festival at the Hollywood Bowl for 17
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 1235 </TRAILER>
