<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Year in the Life of P.D. James  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Readers of a diary kept by British mystery
writer P.D. James may be amazed at the large number of speeches she
gave and the many meetings, dinners, book signings and festivities
she attended over a period of one year. Perhaps more amazing, given
her age and occupation: It was her first diary.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're perpetually asked to do things,'' the 79-year-old James
said. ''Some are very good, charitable things, supporting causes
I'm glad to support. The result is an overly busy life.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Time to Be in Earnest: A Fragment of Autobiography'' was
published by Knopf in April. Besides the activities of her day,
Phyllis Dorothy James also recorded her memories, observations and
opinions in the year between her 77th and 78th birthdays, from Aug.
3, 1997 to Aug. 3, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it should be what I felt at the end of each day,''
she said in an interview. ''Once I wrote, I never revised.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers have been especially interested in her views on the
craft of writing, her childhood memories and her experiences during
the bombing of London in World War II, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In her diary, James deplores the lack of control a writer has
when his or her works are adapted for television or film. She also
writes that she dislikes people who talk loudly on cell phones in
train compartments.
</P>
<P>
   James has enjoyed a long and productive career. Her first book,
''Cover Her Face,'' was published in 1962. A string of best-selling
mysteries followed, bringing her fame and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   She is currently finishing book No. 17, which stars Commander
Adam Dalgliesh, the Scotland Yard detective and published poet, who
is one of the best-known and most interesting creations in popular
English fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ''The chief joy of fame is the private satisfaction that you
have exercised, I think, a God-given talent,'' she said. ''It's the
recognition of talent that gives pleasure to many other people.
They let me know it, and I appreciate that and their support and
encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   Although fame ''does attract a certain amount of envy and
malice, I've been lucky,'' she said. ''There has been very, very
little.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the money, it allows her to help her family and is
assurance that she will never be a financial burden to them. It has
also enabled her to live comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't lived vastly differently on a day-by-day basis, but
it's wonderful to be relieved of the anxiety of being poor,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Queen Elizabeth II made James a baroness, not for her
writing but for her large amount of official public work.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always felt that women were underrepresented on more
powerful bodies. So when I received invitations to serve on things,
I felt I had an obligation to say 'yes' if I thought I could do it.
It's no good complaining and not accepting when you get the
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, she accepts fewer engagements.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have the excuse that I'm nearly 80 now and have to cut down
a bit. I need to conserve my energy for my writing and see more of
friends and family,'' said James, who has two daughters and five
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   As she gets older, James said she has a greater appreciation of
the people she loves. ''One cares less about superficial things,
like what people think. I'm much more aware of the beauty of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ''In youth, one is so busy earning a living and with personal
relationships. Now I get much more pleasure in looking at a cherry
tree in bloom or a tulip.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a family dinner to celebrate her 80th birthday in
August, and Faber and Faber, her English publisher, will host a
party on a boat on the Thames River in London.
</P>
<P>
   James said her age makes her think about the inevitability of
death -- and that so few years remain.
</P>
<P>
   ''Am I going to be writing at 90? Will I write two or three more
books, or less?''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what change during her lifetime upset her the most,
James replied that it is the breakup of the family as an
institution.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was in school from age 5 to 16, there was not a single
child there whose parents were separated or divorced,'' she said.
''I'm not saying divorce is always wrong. With cruelty or terrible
meanness, divorce is the answer. But it seems to me now that
society is much less stable because the family is less strong and
children have suffered very much through this.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every good has its other side. The good is women aren't tied
in economic dependence to staying in an unhappy situation. The
other side is that we have a generation of less happy and less
stable children. There's far more mental illness and suicide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 1237 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deep Purple Is Still Making Music  </HEADLINE>
By GERARD O'LEARY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In 1969, Deep Purple performed ''Concerto for
Group and Orchestra'' with the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra at
Royal Albert Hall in London. Things didn't go exactly as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ''The orchestra did not want to play with us because we were a
rock group,'' recalled bassist Roger Glover during a recent
interview. ''Some members of the orchestra actually walked out,
refusing to play, and the ones that stayed didn't perform well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lead singer Ian Gillan regrets that he didn't take the incident
more seriously, but ''we were just kids basically and weren't
mature enough to handle the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Last September, the band returned to Royal Albert Hall to record
the concerto for a live album. This time, they performed with the
London Symphony Orchestra conducted by Paul Mann.
</P>
<P>
   ''Deep Purple -- Live at the Royal Albert Hall'' (Spitfire
Records) is a two-disc enhanced set with video. Special guests
included Ronnie James Dio, Sam Brown and Eddie Hardin. The album
contains the concerto, ''Smoke on the Water'' and other Deep Purple
hits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bands like Metallica have done the orchestra thing,'' said
guitarist Steve Morse, who joined Deep Purple in 1994. ''But the
difference is they used it to sweeten the songs and make them
fuller. With the concerto, the band is backing the orchestra up and
coming in and out at different times.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover, 54, said it was nostalgic to go back and play at Royal
Albert Hall. ''There is no place like it in the world. ... It is a
totally awe-inspiring building with its beauty and its grandeur.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the passage of time brought any changes?
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the most noticeable differences between now and then is
we're older than most of the orchestra members,'' he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Purple was born in England in 1968. The original members
included guitarist Ritchie Blackmore, drummer Ian Paice,
keyboardist Jon Lord, vocalist Rod Evans and bassist Nick Simper,
who was replaced by Glover.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were originally defined as a progressive band, then an
underground band, hard rock band, then heavy metal,'' said Gillan,
who joined the band in 1969, replacing Evans. ''But I feel we don't
fall in any one category. As my wife once said, 'Deep Purple is
just Deep Purple.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bickering and frequent changes in the band's lineup
over the past 32 years, Deep Purple has recorded hit albums,
including ''Fireball'' (1971), ''Machine Head'' (1972) and
''Perfect Strangers'' (1984), and maintained its popularity with
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's because the band has accepted the need to change that we
have such a large fan base,'' Gillan said. ''It's been like a
roller coaster ride with this band. There has been three definite
highs in the band and three definite lows. ... Maybe four.''
</P>
<P>
   One high was the release of ''Machine Head,'' an album that
catapulted Deep Purple to superstar status and inspired ''Smoke on
the Water,'' a song about a casino in Montreux, Switzerland that
caught fire during a Frank Zappa show. Deep Purple had planned to
use the casino to record ''Machine Head,'' but had to find another
location.
</P>
<P>
   The band split up, then got back together for its ''Perfect
Strangers'' album. In a 1985 AP interview, Glover explained what
led to the breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ''Silly little things that normally you'd work out never got
worked out because of the amount of pressure on us to perform
concerts. Jon Lord said it was death by 1,000 cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody got tired of everybody. Ian Gillan was the first to
say he was leaving. I decided to leave at the same time. I thought
it would be easier on the others. They carried on a while with
replacements. Then Ritchie Blackmore left 18 months later. They
carried on with a replacement for him as well. The whole thing
folded in 1976,'' Glover told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Purple's current lineup is four-fifths the same as the
''classic'' 1969 edition, featuring Gillan, Glover, Paice and Lord,
who composed the ''Concerto for Group and Orchestra.'' Only
Blackmore is missing. He left after the 1993 album ''The Battle
Rages On.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Ritchie is no different from anyone else,'' Glover said. ''We
all have our ups and downs. There are times he is easy to get along
with and times when he is tough. ... I think he kinda enjoys that
reputation and works at maintaining it.''
</P>
<P>
   The chill from the open windows in a freezing hotel room in
midtown Manhattan grew colder when the conversation turned to
Blackmore, the reclusive and often moody guitar virtuoso.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one is asking those questions these days,'' snapped Gillan
in an intimidating tone.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for Spitfire Records is:
http://www.spitfirerecords.com
</P>
<P>
   The home page for Deep Purple is: http://www.deep-purple.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
