<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollster: New York Senate race still a dead heat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Rep. Rick Lazio is running even with Hillary
Rodham Clinton in their U.S. Senate race, just as his predecessor
Rudolph Giuliani was doing when he dropped out of the contest last
month, a new poll indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and Clinton were each favored by 44 percent of voters in
the Quinnipiac University Polling Institute survey released
Wednesday. A Quinnipiac poll released May 16 had Clinton at 44
percent and the New York City mayor at 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Giuliani dropped out of the campaign to battle
prostate cancer. Lazio, a Long Island congressman, got into the
race the same day.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's becoming obvious that the more people get to know Rick,
the more they like him,'' said Lazio campaign spokesman Dan
McLagan.
</P>
<P>
   But McLagan said Lazio does not want to focus on polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to be a tight race and we're going to go up and
down and back and forth with the polls,'' McLagan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign countered that Lazio's poll numbers will
sag as the race continues.
</P>
<P>
   ''As New Yorkers learn more about Lazio's record of voting
against the interests of New York's working families ... they will
realize that Hillary Clinton is the only candidate in this race who
will fight the right fights for New York's children and families,''
Clinton campaign spokeswoman Karen Finney said.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac polling institute in
Hamden, Conn., said that while Lazio's campaign remains a ''work in
progress, 44-44 is a pretty good place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   One cause for Lazio's concern, however, is the fact that 50
percent of those who said they were voting for him are doing so to
vote against Clinton, Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   An anti-Clinton vote is ''not necessarily a bad thing'' for
Lazio, ''but it shows they don't have much of an image of him,''
the pollster said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the voters who stated a preference between Lazio and Clinton,
29 percent of Lazio voters said they strongly favor the Republican
candidate while 57 percent of the Clinton voters said they strongly
favor the Democratic first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Black voters favored Clinton, 83 percent to 7 percent, and Jews
were with her, 44 percent to 37 percent. Whites favored Lazio, 52
percent to 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 970 registered New York voters was
conduced by May 30-June 5 and has a margin of error of plus or
minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
