<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRS agent says Pirro ledgers show unsupported changes  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - A handwritten ''2'' was changed to a
''4'' on an accountant's worksheet, adding a phantom $20,000 to
Albert Pirro's tax deductions in 1994, an Internal Revenue Service
agent testified Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the agent testified, a federal prosecutor displayed the
ledger entry to the jury at Pirro's tax evasion trial, clearly
showing the 2 under the 4 in the work papers of Anthony Pirro,
Albert's accountant, brother and codefendant. There was no
testimony about who might have changed the numeral.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro, husband of Westchester District Attorney Jeanine
Pirro, and his brother are accused of hiding more than $1 million
with phony tax deductions. The trial entered its third week on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   IRS agent John Dennehy, in his third day on the stand, said the
overwritten ''2'' changed a depreciation entry from $23,613 to
$43,613 and bumped the total allowance to $73,123 instead of the
$53,123 that could have properly been taken.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, that cut Pirro's declared income by $20,000, Dennehy
said.
</P>
<P>
   The accountant's papers showed other mysterious entries, Dennehy
said. An extra $23,455 in interest expenses, $30,000 in
subcontracting expenses and $10,588 in rent was added, without
foundation, to various companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Was there any explanation?'' asked Assistant U.S. Attorney
Cathy Seibel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just the figure,'' Dennehy said. The effect, he said again,
was to cut Pirro's declared income and thereby limit his tax
liability.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he said, a company half-owned by Pirro was entitled to
a $517 deduction for ''passive activity loss'' but took $30,517,
reducing Pirro's income by $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   The agent also presented a computerized slide show purporting to
show that the $45,000 decorative gates outside the Pirro home in
Harrison were paid for in a complex transaction using three of
Pirro's companies. The gates were amortized by two companies,
resulting in improper deductions, he said, because the gates were a
personal expense.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about defense claims that the gates were for the district
attorney's security, Dennehy said they were designed long before
she became district attorney, were not very secure and were not
reported on her tax return the year they were paid for.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Pirro has not been accused.
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy also testified that Albert Pirro improperly deducted as
entertainment 50 percent of the $5,000 in dues he paid in 1995 for
Donald Trump's Mar-a-Lago beach club in Palm Beach, Fla., near the
Pirros' summer home.
</P>
<P>
   And he noted that there was overdraft protection on some of
Pirro's accounts; in 1995, his personal corporation account was
overdrawn by as much as $37,000. A secretary testified earlier that
personal expenses were paid from business accounts only if there
was not enough money in the personal account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
