<DOCNO> APW20000607.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 20; Nasdaq Up 11  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned slightly higher in a quiet session
today as investors awaited word on Microsoft's antitrust case and
looked for new ways to buy into the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   In early afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 19.58 at 10,755.15.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 7.01 at 1,464.85, and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 10.96 at 3,767.33.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell 75 cents to $68.875. After the close of trading
today, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson was expected to
issue his ruling on whether to split the computer software company
into two separate businesses. Microsoft has previously said it will
appeal any order to break it up.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology companies were faring better. Microstrategy,
a software maker that has struggled since admitting it would have
to restate earnings for the past few years, rose $9.688 to $37.688.
Traders said the company may receive financing from an outside
source.
</P>
<P>
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines rose $2.50 to $29. KLM and British
Airways confirmed they have begun talks that could lead to a
merger. An alliance would create the world's third-largest airline,
behind United Airlines and American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways fell 56.25 cents to $59.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, trading was quiet and directionless, with market
averages changing course several times. Analysts said interest rate
worries, which eased last week amid a slew of reports that signaled
a modest economic slowdown, haven't truly left the market. Many
investors are back on the sidelines, waiting for more information
as they try to discern whether the Fed may finally be finished
raising interest rates to cool the pace of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Federal Reserve Governor Laurence Meyer said the Fed
may have to force U.S. economic growth to a more substantial
slowdown. But he said he believes the slowdown can take place
without derailing the economy's expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Several considerations provide optimism that the outcome will
be a benign one -- a soft landing as opposed to a hard landing,''
Meyer told the Boston Economics Club.
</P>
<P>
   The next crucial piece of data for Fed economists and investors
will be the Producer Price Index, due out Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues barely outnumbered advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 539.94 million shares, well
behind Tuesday's moderate pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.94 to 510.71.
</P>
<P>
   ------
