<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korean War Remembrance Opens  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Air Force leaders opened their remembrance of
the Korean War by warning that some of the same threats to
readiness that hampered the U.S. military in that conflict 50 years
ago are repeating themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''If ever there was a lesson learned in the cost of letting
readiness slide, Korea is it,'' Secretary of the Air Force F.
Whitten Peters said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Peters noted that when the war started on June 25, 1950, the Air
Force, like the other U.S. armed services, had just ''drawn down
rapidly after the victory of World War II and as a result was
unprepared in many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Michael Ryan said military budgets
also were historically low, as they are again today.
</P>
<P>
   ''History teaches us a lot of lessons if we'll just listen,''
Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating themes that are some of the main issues facing the
services today, the two top men at the Air Force spoke at a daylong
seminar on the 1950-53 war, which ended not in victory, but with a
truce that has left the peninsula divided between communist North
Korea and Democratic South.
</P>
<P>
   The seminar is the first in a series of events this month that
will commemorate the outbreak of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said the military budget at the start of the Korean War was
at its ''second lowest level'' since the attack on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''And the first lowest point since Pearl Harbor is today ...
about 3 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was also fought during a time when the strategic interests
of the United States were stated in an unfortunate way -- where the
question of our resolve to be able to prosecute the conflict was in
question, not only within the United States, but transmitted
outside the United States in a very clear way,'' Ryan said. ''And
today we find ourselves in that same debate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
