<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorneys give closing arguments in insurance magnate's fraud case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - A businessman was guilty of bad decisions
- not fraud, embezzlement and tax evasion - in the collapse of his
insurance empire, a defense attorney told a federal court jury
Wednesday as it prepared for deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Michael Koening told the U.S. District Court
panel to focus on defendant Albert Lawrence's state of mind as it
considered whether he was guilty of illegally using $32 million in
company assets.
</P>
<P>
   ''What was in Albert Lawrence's mind. It was to save his
company,'' Koening told jurors during an hourlong closing
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Koening reminded jurors that Lawrence acted on the advice of
''big banks, big attorneys and big accountants'' and that the
72-year-old insurance magnate went from a worth of $150 million to
bankruptcy trying to save his ailing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''He made errors in judgment. He made bad business decisions,''
said Koening. ''But he never intended to harm anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, of Schenectady, was named in a 20-count indictment
charging him with embezzlement, mail and wire fraud, and tax
evasion. Lawrence, once head of the now-defunct Lawrence Group
Inc., a holding company that owned most of the insurance companies,
is accused of illegally using $32 million in assets that should
have been invested to cover future policyholder claims.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lawrence used the money in an attempt to salvage his
own financially troubled companies and for his own benefit,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence's Schenectady-based insurance companies operated in
dozens of states. The businesses have since either been liquidated
or sold.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence could face a maximum of 50 years in prison and fines of
millions of dollars if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Frederick Scullin was scheduled to give jurors legal
instructions Wednesday and then send them off to begin
deliberations. The jury began hearing testimony May 9.
</P>
<P>
   During his closing argument, Assistant U.S. Attorney William
Pericak repeatedly used the words ''schemed'' and ''connived'' as
he stressed to jurors how Lawrence had used the money illegally and
then tried to cover his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you determine someone's intent, you do it at the time of
their actions, not after the fact,'' Pericak said. ''He put his own
interests first, second, third and fourth. His actions speak louder
than his words.''
</P>
<P>
   Pericak said prosecution evidence showed that Lawrence had ample
financial resources to keep his companies solvent. He said Lawrence
offered no legal defense during his testimony, only weak
explanations.
</P>
<P>
   Pericak told jurors not to believe the defense's assertion that
Lawrence acted on the advice of others.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Lawrence was the boss,'' Pericak said. ''He hired several
employees as high-paid yes men who told him what he wanted to
hear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
