<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regents to consider vocational diploma  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - High school students seeking a vocational
curriculum will have the option of getting a technical endorsement
on their diploma, according to a proposal being presented to the
state Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, students wishing to pursue a trade could take
integrated programs that will combine academic learning with
technical skills. The programs would be designed by schools and
boards of cooperative education services (BOCES) and would need
certification from the state Education Department to become
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Students would also have to complete industry-based technical
assessments, to be developed either internally by the state
Education Department, by external groups, or both.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, schools and BOCES would prepare a ''work skills and
employability profile'' for each student based on the individual's
technical achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Graduating students who complete the integrated programs and
technical assessments would receive a ''career and technical
endorsement'' on their high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, devised by two panels of statewide and national
experts, was presented to the Regents last Friday and will be taken
up during the board's meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
   Education officials said such programs would address critics'
concerns that the Regent's tougher educational standards are not
giving vocational students enough time to learn adequate technical
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ''This proposal would help solve the important issue of time for
students who want a career and technical education,'' state
Education Commissioner Richard Mills said in a statement Wednesday.
''They would be able to learn English, math and other subjects at
the same time and in the same courses in which they learn
vocational skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Schadewald, coordinator of instruction at the Capital
Region BOCES, serving Albany, Schenectady, Saratoga and Schoharie
counties, said without integrated programs, Regents requirements
are putting teachers and counselors in a ''crunch.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now there is a lot of stress to get students to get
through the requirements alone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is also getting support from the business
community.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very glad that the Regents are taking this up. It's very
important to businesses that technical education be part of the
standards,'' said Margarita Mayo, Director of Education Training
for the Business Council of New York State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-07-00 1448 </TRAILER>
