<HEADLINE> Drug Offers Hope Vs. Scleroderma  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A synthetic version of a fertility hormone
reverses some of the crippling, disfiguring effects of the
sometimes-fatal tissue disease scleroderma, researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   A study in Tuesday's Annals of Internal Medicine found in most
patients, a low dose of the hormone relaxin softened and loosened
skin scarred and hardened by the poorly understood disease.
</P>
<P>
   Caused by unexplained overproduction of the protein collagen,
the ''scaffold'' supporting tissue, scleroderma afflicts about
400,000 Americans to some degree, mostly women of childbearing age.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-patient study is the first in which patients getting a
drug improved more than a comparison group getting a placebo, lead
researcher Dr. James R. Seibold said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a bit of an historic first,'' said Seibold, director of
the Scleroderma Research Center at the University of Medicine and
Dentistry of New Jersey in New Brunswick. ''We see softening of the
skin. Patients are able to use their hands better, their ability to
perform basic tasks of daily activity improves, they're able to
open their mouths better.''
</P>
<P>
   Scleroderma can make fingers and other joints inflexible,
leaving patients unable to eat, groom themselves or do other basic
tasks unassisted. Often, it hardens internal organs, the esophagus,
gastrointestinal tract and blood vessels, making it difficult for
the body to breathe, deliver oxygen to tissues, clear out toxins,
or swallow or absorb food.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it kills quickly. Current treatments can only relieve
some symptoms. Unlike relaxin, many of those have nasty side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. E. Carwil LeRoy, professor and chairman of microbiology and
immunology at the Medical University of South Carolina, said
relaxin has a good track record of inhibiting collagen formation in
test tube and animal experiments and appears to reverse damage to
skin. But he said more research is needed, particularly to see
whether it can stop or reverse the internal damage some patients
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, groups of patients received a low dose of relaxin,
a dose four times higher, or a benign, sterile solution.
</P>
<P>
   After six months, patients getting the placebo and the high dose
fared about the same, with a few getting worse and nearly half
showing no improvement. Just over half the patients getting the low
dose improved greatly; a few more improved only somewhat, and none
got worse.
</P>
<P>
   A one-year, 185-patient study is planned to learn more about
relaxin's long-term effects. Other studies are under way.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is being developed by Connetics Corp., a California
company that is funding the research. John Higgins, president of
the company, said Connetics plans to test relaxin in people with
life-threatening poor leg circulation, infertility and two other
conditions that occur alone or as part of scleroderma, fibrosis of
the kidneys and of the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.scleroderma.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.connetics.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 1450 </TRAILER>
