<HEADLINE> Murder, Mayhem Returns to Colosseum  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Murder and mayhem are returning to the Colosseum,
1,500 years after the last gladiators fought and died in the
ancient arena. But this time the blood is fake and so are the
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The ruins will form the backdrop for productions of three Greek
tragedies by Sophocles, ''Oedipus the King,'' ''Antigone'' and
''Oedipus at Colonus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ministry of Culture and the National Institute of Ancient
Drama on Wednesday announced the productions, which will run from
July 19 to Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Colosseum, ancient Rome's most famous monument, was the
scene of bloody gladiator fights for hundreds of years until they
were banned in the 5th century, about 40 years before the fall of
the Roman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   The last known spectacle in the amphitheater, fights between men
and wild beasts, took place in A.D. 523 during the reign of
Theodoric, king of the Ostrogoths.
</P>
</TEXT>
