<HEADLINE> Democrats Push Equal Pay for Women  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats are urging House Republicans to act
soon on proposals to narrow the wage gap for women.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said House GOP leaders should follow the lead of
moderate Republican Sen. James Jeffords of Vermont, who scheduled a
Thursday hearing before his Health, Education, Labor and Pensions
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should do the same in the House,'' Rep. Rosa DeLauro,
D-Conn., said Wednesday. ''Unequal pay is unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Eleanor Holmes Norton, the District of Columbia's delegate
to Congress and a former head of the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission: ''Congress must not go home for the July 4 recess
without making a start on fair pay for American women and their
families.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, women earn about 75 percent as much as equally
qualified men, according to a variety of government and independent
studies. Several proposals in Congress would tighten controls and
enforcement of federal equal pay laws.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has sought about $47 million to help narrow
the wage gap for women, including money to advance the careers of
women in the high technology field.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., chairman of the House
Education and the Workforce Committee, House Democratic leader Dick
Gephardt of Missouri and 20 colleagues wrote that Congress should
''send a strong message to American women -- and to their families --
that we value their work and that we will do what it takes to
ensure that they are paid equally for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
