<HEADLINE> Dow Up 92; Nasdaq Up 11  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mostly higher in a quiet session
today as investors awaited word on Microsoft's antitrust case and
looked for new ways to buy into the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 91.92 at 10,827.49.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 7.01 at 1,464.85, and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 10.96 at 3,767.33.
</P>
<P>
   Market averages broke out of a tight trading range as investors
bought a wide range of technology stocks. IBM rose $6.688 to
$119.063, contributing most to the Dow's gains, after Goldman Sachs
analyst Laura Conigliaro said orders were strong in the past two
months.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology companies were also faring better.
Microstrategy, a software maker that has struggled since admitting
it would have to restate earnings for the past few years, rose
$8.438 to $36.438. Traders said the company may receive financing
from an outside source.
</P>
<P>
   And biotechnology stocks continued their most recent winning
streak. Immunex rose $4.063 to $36.188 after the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration expanded its approval of the company's Enbrel
rheumatoid arthritis drug to more patients.
</P>
<P>
   The good news from a diverse range of technology companies
helped distract investors from their concerns over Microsoft. After
the close of trading today, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson was expected to issue his ruling on whether to split the
computer software company into two separate businesses. Microsoft
has previously said it will appeal any order to break it up.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose 25 cents to $69.875.
</P>
<P>
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines rose $2.50 to $29. KLM and British
Airways confirmed they have begun talks that could lead to a
merger. An alliance would create the world's third-largest airline,
behind United Airlines and American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways fell 56.25 cents to $59.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, trading was quiet. Analysts said interest rate
worries, which eased last week amid a slew of reports that signaled
a modest economic slowdown, haven't truly left the market. Many
investors are back on the sidelines, waiting for more information
as they try to discern whether the Fed may finally be finished
raising interest rates to cool the pace of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Federal Reserve Governor Laurence Meyer said the Fed
may have to force U.S. economic growth to a more substantial
slowdown. But he said he believes the slowdown can take place
without derailing the economy's expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Several considerations provide optimism that the outcome will
be a benign one -- a soft landing as opposed to a hard landing,''
Meyer told the Boston Economics Club.
</P>
<P>
   The next crucial piece of data for Fed economists and investors
will be the Producer Price Index, due out Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues barely outnumbered advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 656.47 million shares, well
behind Tuesday's moderate pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.00 to 512.65.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
