<HEADLINE> Swedes Deliver Unpretentious Jazz  </HEADLINE>
by 
V0265-----
r e *1403AP-Swedish-Jazz     06-07 0447
*1403 AP-Swedish-Jazz,0446   
Swedes Deliver Unpretentious Jazz   
An AP Entertainment Review
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It was just jazz -- straightforward,
unpretentious. But what the Swedish musicians delivered Tuesday at
Carnegie Hall, in a kind of prelude to the 12-day JVC Jazz
Festival, was of quality that the festival's participants may find
difficult to match.
</P>
<P>
   All evening, Swedish musicians in various groups made
straightforward jazz interesting, playing with skill, feeling and
fluency. They improvised and didn't overembroider; they played a
lot more clarinet than one gets from American jazz concerts these
days. All in all, they were more interested in the fine quality of
the cloth than the decoration.
</P>
<P>
   The concert, hosted by Duke Ellington's granddaughter Mercedes
Ellington, began with ''Deep Purple'' by the Swedish Swing Society,
doing a good job of portraying the Benny Goodman Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   Next came a tribute to Dixieland from the five-member Stockholm
Classic Jazz Band, playing banjo and a muted trumpet that sounded
as tinny as an early New Orleans recording.
</P>
<P>
   Small groups shone: the Allan-Gustafsson-Riedel Quartet with Jan
Allan playing light but assured trumpet on ''Sweet and Lovely'' to
easy, dissonant accompaniment; followed by ''Toomba Samba''
composed by bassist Georg Riedel.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday Night Big Band ended the first half of the concert in
emphatic but non-derivative American big-band style.
</P>
<P>
   The second half was even better. Pianist Jan Lundgren's trio
began with a gentle composition of his ''A Touch of You,'' in Bill
Evans' style. A guest, guitarist Ulf Wakenius, joined them for
''Cakewalk,'' which Lundgren played in Oscar Peterson's style, and
Wakenius played ''Too Late Now'' as a solo, with soft, full, round
tones.
</P>
<P>
   The Putte Wickman and Claes Crona Trio moved the evening in a
more modern, less melodically intent direction with two
compositions by pianist Crona. Then, while Crona improvised,
clarinettist Wickman played ''I Loves You, Porgy'' with tonal
beauty. They finished by making ''Summertime'' swing, Wickman
noodling a final phrase of great originality.
</P>
<P>
   A tribute to Jazz at the Philharmonic had a guitarist,
clarinettist, trombonist and three saxophonists lined up across the
stage. Organist Kjell Ohman and vibraphonist Lars Erstrand were
exceptional. Two singers appeared briefly -- the clear, flexible
soprano Rigmor Gustafsson, and Svante Thuresson, whose vocal style
is rooted in blues.
</P>
<P>
   The June 12-24 JVC festival opens Monday at the Kaye Playhouse
with a tribute to pianist Bill Evans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 1612 </TRAILER>
