<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New trial sought for murder on racial bias claim  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - A convicted murderer is seeking a new
trial because his defense lawyer was not allowed to ask prospective
jurors their opinions on interracial marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Frank Mandanici said the interracial marriage question
can act as ''the X-ray of the heart'' to get at whether a person is
racially biased.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're against interracial marriage, I believe that means
you're a racist at heart,'' said Mandanici, a public defender in
New Haven Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on race relations disagree about whether opposition to
interracial marriage always indicates someone is biased and would
be unfit to serve on a jury where a black person is accused of a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Something about the issue, however, seems to spark more
controversy- among people of all races - than other racially
charged matters, such as integrated schools, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Mandanici is making such an argument in a 13-page brief before
U.S. District Judge Alvin W. Thompson in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   In picking a jury in 1990 for the murder trial of Sean Smith,
who is black, Mandanici asked jurors several questions about race.
When he asked about interracial marriage, the prosecutor objected
and the judge told Mandanici to withdraw the question.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was convicted of killing Darrel Brantley in Meriden and
was sentenced to 40 years in prison. Smith claimed he acted in
self-defense when he shot and killed Brantley in 1990. Mandanici
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Connecticut Supreme Court found that while the
question was proper, it did not matter in Smith's case because
other questions about racial attitudes had been asked.
</P>
<P>
   Mandanici and other lawyers now can freely ask about interracial
marriages when picking juries. Mandanici said the issue is
important enough to warrant a new trial for Smith.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal appeal, he says the recent controversy about Bob
Jones University's policy against interracial dating shows how the
issue indicates overall racial attitudes in a way that other issues
cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a policy against interracial marriages is such a litmus
test that the government can expel a university from the rolls of
tax-exempt institutions ... then surely a defendant in a criminal
case should be allowed to apply the same litmus test and expel
potential jurors,'' Mandanici wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to interracial marriage cuts across all races,
experts on race relations said, and is probably the prevailing
public opinion today.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you get jurors who all favor interracial marriage, you'll
have a stacked jury. The people who favor it are not with
mainstream values,'' said University of Delaware history professor
Raymond Wolters.
</P>
<P>
   Wolters also pointed out that some prominent black leaders have
been opposed to interracial marriage for nonbiased reasons.
</P>
<P>
   W.E.B. Du Bois thought mixed-race marriages were likely to fail
because social conditions made it very difficult for the couples to
be secure in their marriages and raise their children, Wolters
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other leaders, such as Marcus Garvey, opposed interracial
marriage because of their pride in the black race, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors who are asked about interracial marriage give all kinds
of answers to explain their opposition, such as ''the Bible says
it's wrong'' or ''people should stay with their own kind.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the religion angle is way to justify what can't
otherwise be justified. Who's going to argue with God?'' asked
Robert McNamara, a sociology professor at Furman College in South
Carolina, who wrote the book ''Crossing the Line: Interracial
Couples in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   McNamara said opinions such as Du Bois' just show that the
problems interracial couples and children face are not because of
race, but because of the way a biased society treats them.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of the reasons people use to oppose interracial
marriages are flawed or rationalizations to hide what's really
under the surface - that they think blacks and whites shouldn't
marry because blacks are inferior,'' McNamara said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
