<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 77; Nasdaq Up 83  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks shook off early losses to
close higher today after a Goldman Sachs analyst said IBM is
expected to have a strong year. The rosy prospects for IBM helped
pull investors off the sidelines, where they had been fitfully
awaiting a judge's ruling on Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stocks came on very strongly once they found a catalyst,''
said Scott Bleier, chief investment strategist at Prime Charter
Ltd. in New York. ''It wasn't anything terribly dramatic, but
there's a lot of money on the sidelines, and a fervent desire to
get it to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 77.29 to 10,812.86, while
the Nasdaq composite index rose 82.76 to 3,839.13. Both indexes
recovered from early declines.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 13.52 to 1,471.36.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,604 up, 1,323 down and 493
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 840.19 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.
936.15 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.89 to 516.54.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market seems to be on the path of least resistance, and
that is to the upside,'' said Bleier, noting that investors are
continuing to buy stocks even after solid gains last week that
could have set up a big bout of profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks continued a steady recovery from their swoon in
March and April, led by IBM. Well-known Goldman Sachs analyst Laura
Conigliaro said orders were strong in the past two months, and
added that investors may be undervaluing the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology companies were also faring better.
Microstrategy, a software maker that has struggled since admitting
it would have to restate earnings for the past few years, rose
sharply as investors anticipated that the company may soon receive
financing from an outside source.
</P>
<P>
   And biotechnology stocks continued their most recent winning
streak. Immunex rose after the U.S. Food and Drug Administration
expanded its approval of the company's Enbrel rheumatoid arthritis
drug to more patients.
</P>
<P>
   The good news from a diverse range of technology companies
helped distract investors from their concerns over Microsoft. After
the close of trading today, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson was expected to issue his ruling on whether to split the
computer software company into two separate businesses. Microsoft
has previously said it will appeal any order to break it up.
</P>
<P>
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines rose. KLM and British Airways confirmed
they have begun talks that could lead to a merger. An alliance
would create the world's third-largest airline, behind United
Airlines and American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways ended with a more modest gain.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, trading was quiet. Analysts said interest rate
worries, which eased last week amid a slew of reports that signaled
a modest economic slowdown, haven't truly left the market. Many
investors are back on the sidelines, waiting for more information
as they try to discern whether the Fed may finally be finished
raising interest rates to cool the pace of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Federal Reserve Governor Laurence Meyer said the Fed
may have to force U.S. economic growth to a more substantial
slowdown. But he said he believes the slowdown can take place
without derailing the economy's expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Several considerations provide optimism that the outcome will
be a benign one -- a soft landing as opposed to a hard landing,''
Meyer told the Boston Economics Club.
</P>
<P>
   The next crucial piece of data for Fed economists and investors
will be the Producer Price Index, due out Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
