<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Trial Focuses on Fragment  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- It's just a tiny piece of
evidence the size of a fingernail. But prosecutors hope it pays off
big in linking two Libyan defendants to the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103.
</P>
<P>
   The Lockerbie trial, in its sixth week, moved to a new stage
Wednesday by focusing on a half-inch fragment of a circuit board
that appears to have belonged to the electronic timer that
detonated the Lockerbie bomb.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the two suspects planted the bomb
with the detonator on a connecting flight from the Mediterranean
island of Malta. Investigators have traced the detonator to a Swiss
firm that said it delivered a batch of the timers to Libyan
intelligence agents who allegedly worked with the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the trial has involved a description and analysis of
the debris from the explosion Dec. 21, 1988, over Lockerbie,
Scotland that killed 270 people, including 189 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, described
in their indictment as Libyan intelligence officers, have pleaded
innocent, blaming Palestinian terrorist groups for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Alan Turnbull showed the Scottish court photo
enlargements of the circuit board fragment with blackened bumpy
edges. A silver painted ''1,'' possibly all that was left of an
identification code, spanned the blistered top surface beside two
copper foil leads.
</P>
<P>
   Glasgow police inspector Keith Harrower told the court that in
the four months following the discovery of the fragment in January
1990 he went to electronics firms in Britain and Germany to try to
learn where the board had come from.
</P>
<P>
   But by April 1990 the search still had not uncovered the
manufacturer and the investigation was handed over to other
Scottish investigators, Harrower said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not say whether the fragment was the one
identified by investigators in 1991 as a piece of the
Swiss-manufactured electronic timer that triggered the bomb 38
minutes after the jetliner took off from London's Heathrow Airport
en route to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss timer was cited as a key piece of evidence when U.S.
and British authorities announced the indictment against the two
Libyans in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbull, the prosecutor, indicated he would try to establish a
link between the detonator and the Libyan intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   The Lockerbie trial is being conducted before a special Scottish
court at this former U.S. air base as a result of an agreement that
persuaded Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi to surrender the suspects
after nearly a decade of economic sanctions in his country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
