<DOCNO> APW20000607.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCall says Pataki, Legislature missed boat on budget  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki and the state Legislature
missed an opportunity to provide significant long-term stability to
state finances in the recently enacted budget, state Comptroller H.
Carl McCall said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said the 2000-01 budget displayed a ''business-as-usual''
attitude, while the state's strong tax collections and continuing
surpluses should have dictated a more prudent, farsighted approach.
</P>
<P>
   McCall's analysis, which was attacked by the Pataki
administration, said the $77.5 billion budget fails to close
projected future-year budget gaps, borrows too much, has a spending
increase far higher than the rate of inflation and ''backloads''
tax cuts so that they don't take full effect for three or four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a classic recipe for creating failed policies for the
future,'' McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and Legislature, with a $1.5 billion budget surplus
at the end of the last fiscal year, should have put far more money
into reserve funds as a hedge against a future economic downturn,
McCall said. The comptroller also faulted the budget for failing to
address a long-standing budget shortfall involving the State
University of New York's hospitals and to make changes in the
state's aid-to-education formulas.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic comptroller's analysis was assailed by the
Republican Pataki administration, which noted that McCall may end
up running against Pataki for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a blatantly political and partisan report from someone
who is running for office,'' state Budget Division spokesman Joe
Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   McCall fails to give Pataki credit for the five years of tax
cutting he has done as governor, nor for getting the Legislature to
adopt a debt-reform package as part of the budget which should
curtail some borrowing by New York, Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   ''On debt reform in particular, New Yorkers should be made aware
of the fact that the comptroller was nowhere to be found when
Governor Pataki was fighting a tough and ultimately successful
battle to achieve the first real reforms in state history,'' Conway
said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget spokesman said Pataki successfully closed a projected
$5 billion budget gap during the first state budget he presided
over, for fiscal 1995-96, and that New York has earned two credit
upgrades on Wall Street since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think his fiscal track record speaks for itself,'' Conway
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCall spokesman Jeffrey Gordon countered it is unfair to take a
shot against McCall on debt reform since the comptroller has pushed
for changing the state's borrowing practices for years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Parts of that package were lifted directly'' from the reform
provisions McCall has been favoring, Gordon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-07-00 1657 </TRAILER>
