<HEADLINE> Insurgents ask for details on $1 billion in budget  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Democratic insurgents in the state Assembly
asked Wednesday for details on how more than $1 billion included in
the new state budget will be spent, and who will spend it.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen Democratic Assembly members who comprise the Assembly
Majority Reform Caucus said it is unclear how money from several
well-funded state programs in the $77.5 billion budget will be
allocated.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the $350 million Transportation Multi-Modal
Program, $225 million for the Strategic Investment Program, $200
million for the 007-Commnity Projects Fund for member items and
$125 million for the Transportation Industrial Access Program.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators also asked for how $195 million remaining from
the Community Enhancement Facilities Program in the 1998 budget is
being spent.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry was promised by the insurgent Democrats when they
came out publicly against Sheldon Silver as speaker in the
Assembly. The group called for reforms on how the ruling Democrats
run the Assembly and for Silver to be replaced by the chamber's
ex-majority leader, Michael Bragman.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to topple Silver failed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the group's complaints was that rank-and-file members have
ceded too much control over spending to the majority leaders of the
state Assembly and Senate. Those two legislators and the governor
have acquired virtually unfettered power to spend discretionary
funds totaling hundreds of millions of dollars for each men, the
reform caucus said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The members and the public are entitled'' to information about
the spending of discretionary money, the Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver spokeswoman Patricia Lynch declined comment on the
insurgents' request.
</P>
</TEXT>
