<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujimori Reviews Sec. Chief's Role  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori says it's time for
Vladimiro Montesinos, his shadowy security chief, to step into the
light.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Fujimori said
Montesinos, widely feared for his spy network and the power he
exercises, needs to clear up a broad range of accusations against
him.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the Organization of American States to take
steps to improve democratic rule after his tainted re-election last
month, Fujimori said he was reviewing what role his controversial
spy chief might play in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect that his work will not continue to be secret,''
Fujimori said late Tuesday night at the Government Palace in Lima's
colonial downtown. ''At some moment he should come out into the
public light because he has to clarify all the accusations that
have been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos has been accused of taking money from drug lords,
having links to death squads and spearheading smear campaigns
against Fujimori's opponents in the recent presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Montesinos' dark reputation, Fujimori has kept him close
by during his decade in power because he has proved highly useful
in defeating leftist rebels and undercutting Fujimori's political
opponents, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, a leader who has often blurred the line between
dictator and democrat, admitted that his government was an
''imperfect democracy'' that needed improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there is any country in the world that can say
it has a perfect democracy,'' the 61-year-old, bespectacled
president said.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS on Monday stopped short of questioning Peru's
presidential election or imposing sanctions. Instead it resolved to
send a high-level mission to Peru to work on strengthening
democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said he would welcome and work with the OAS mission but
would not accept its questioning his re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
   He risked turning Peru into a pariah state by going ahead with a
May 28 runoff after his opponent Alejandro Toledo pulled out,
accusing him of planning to rig the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori discussed steps he was planning to strengthen
democratic safeguards in line with OAS demands.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to overhaul the judicial system to assure its
independence, giving special attention to reviving the
Constitutional Tribunal, which among other responsibilities reviews
violations of individual rights and threats to press freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal has been inactive since the Fujimori-controlled
Congress fired three of its seven members in 1997 after they ruled
that Fujimori could not be a candidate for a third consecutive
five-year term. Fujimori proceeded to run despite a constitutional
limit of two straight terms.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more importantly, Fujimori said he planned to
reduce the powers and size of the National Intelligence Service and
reassign excess personnel to other military branches.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence service, under Montesinos' command, has been
accused of spying on opposition politicians and independent
journalists viewed as threats to Fujimori's power. Critics say it
resorts to wiretaps, extortion, even death threats to intimidate
political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori stopped short of saying he might fire Montesinos, but
neither did he rule it out, saying before he takes any action, his
security chief must take steps to clean up his image.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to give Montesinos a lot of credit,'' said Michael
Radu, a senior fellow with the Foreign Policy Research Institute in
Philadelphia, who has studied Peru for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is not there because Fujimori likes him. He is there
because he has performed. He is a very brilliant person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
