<HEADLINE> Blumenthal wants moratorium on tribal recognition decisions  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Attorney General Richard Blumenthal asked
federal officials Wednesday to stop issuing American Indian tribal
recognition decisions until the government figures out how to
better handle the job.
</P>
<P>
   In letters to Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and the co-chairs
of the Senate Indian Affairs Committee, Blumenthal asked for a
moratorium on recognition decisions. He also urged the leaders of
the Senate committee to scrap a proposed bill that would that would
create a three-person commission appointed by the president to
decide which tribes are recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said tribal recognition should be decided by a larger
commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''There should be a moratorium on any recognition decisions and
changes in law until there's a national commission that can asses
the best process for these decisions to be made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal's letters are in response to last month's surprise
announcement by the head of the Bureau of Indian Affairs that his
agency can no longer handle the task of granting federal
recognition to tribes. BIA chief Kevin Gover said he would support
legislation removing the responsibility from his agency.
</P>
<P>
   Federal recognition makes tribes eligible for several federal
assistance programs and classifies them as sovereign nations. With
recognition often comes the power to open a gaming casino.
</P>
<P>
   More than 550 tribes are federally recognized and about 200
cases are pending.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, the Golden Hill Paugusett, Schaghticoke, Eastern
Pequot and Paucatuck Eastern tribes are seeking federal
recognition. The latter two tribes have been granted preliminary
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The BIA requires reams of historical documentation from tribes,
and sometimes takes as long as 12 years to make a decision on a
request for recognition. Critics pressing for change say that's too
long.
</P>
<P>
   Schaghticoke Chief Richard Velky called Blumenthal's request for
a moratorium a ''slowdown tactic.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know how much slower the process can get,'' Velky
said. The Schaghticokes have been waiting more than three years for
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, the Colorado
Republican and co-chair of the Indian Affairs Committee who
proposed the bill to set up a three-person panel to make
recognition decisions, also criticized Blumenthal's requests.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see where Mr. Blumenthal seeks to be helpful,'' the
spokesman, Chris Changery said. ''His requests will just continue
the delays that are already there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-07-00 1747 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trade Supporters Fear Delay  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Supporters of normalizing trade with China
appealed Wednesday to Senate leaders for a final vote before July
4, even if it means accepting all House amendments.
</P>
<P>
   In a closed-door meeting, the Senate Finance Committee agreed to
pursue a no-amendment strategy in hopes of moving the legislation
quickly, said Ginny Flynn, spokeswoman for the committee chairman,
Sen. William Roth, R-Del.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody in the room agreed with that strategy,'' she said.
''The committee is united.''
</P>
<P>
   Prohibiting amendments to speed passage would be highly unusual
in the Senate, which prides itself on being deliberative.
</P>
<P>
   Any changes made by the Senate would require the legislation to
be returned to the House. Also, the Clinton administration and its
congressional allies want to avoid a repeat of the bruising battle
in the House, which approved the legislation 237-197 last month.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is supported by corporate America and most Republicans,
while organized labor, a key Democratic constituency, opposes it
fiercely.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 10 moderate Democrats also delivered the same
no-amendment message Wednesday in letters to Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., and Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. Both leaders
support the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we recognize the importance of Senate prerogatives and
the right of each member to offer amendments, this legislation
merits a bipartisan effort to pass the bill as it has been sent to
us from the House,'' the Democrats wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The House added amendments to provide relief for U.S. industries
battered by surges in low-cost Chinese imports, and to set up a
watchdog commission to monitor human rights and trade practices in
China.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the amendments were crafted carefully to pick up
enough Democratic support to win passage in the House, and that any
changes could mean new troubles for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate completely accepts the House version, the bill
would go right to the president for his certain signature.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would end annual votes on China's trade status and
allow U.S. businesses to take full advantage of China's entry into
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The measure has wide bipartisan support in the Senate, but
opponents have threatened to use delaying tactics. With the
congressional calendar crammed with important spending bills needed
to keep the government functioning after Oct. 1, some lawmakers
have suggested the China bill might have to be delayed until the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 Democrats urged a final vote before July 4 are: Bob
Graham of Florida, John Breaux of Louisiana, Richard Bryan of
Nevada, Max Cleland of Georgia, Tim Johnson of South Dakota, Bob
Kerrey of Nebraska, Mary Landrieu of Louisiana, Joe Lieberman of
Connecticut, Blanche Lincoln of Arkansas and Chuck Robb of
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House site: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO site: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 1748 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-CT--Oyster Funding, 3rd Ld-Writethru, 700  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Twenty-three Connecticut oyster farmers
are being asked to return more than $1 million in federal disaster
aid after the government determined their farming methods don't
conform to federal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for aid, the government requires farmers to raise
oysters in the ''controlled environment'' of cages. The Connecticut
farmers use a ''bottom culture'' method, taking oysters out of
their natural beds. About 90 percent of the sound's oysters are
bottom growers, said Terry Backer, executive director of the
watchdog group Soundkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   The government's demand, state farmers say, threatens their
livelihood. The president of a national industry group says it
poses a threat to oystermen across the country who use the same
farming method and rely on the same federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Long Island Sound was hit by two parasites, commonly
referred to as MSX and Dermo. El Nino conditions caused the water
temperature to rise above normal, triggering the infestation, said
Backer.
</P>
<P>
   Backer, whose family has been in the oyster business since 1820,
received $67,000 of the $1.46 million doled out last year to 23
farmers who qualified through applications based on losses from the
1997 outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ''They issue these payments to us and come back a year later and
say (they) made a horrible mistake and (they) need the money
back,'' said Backer. ''People depended on this money and they spent
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A letter dated June 2 from the Windsor-based Farm Service Agency
of the U.S. Department of Agriculture says, ''The Connecticut State
FSA Committee has reviewed your application for 1998 Crop Loss
Disaster Assistance program (CLDAP) benefits for oysters and has
determined you did not raise the oysters in a controlled
environment ... As a result, the State Committee has also
determined that you were overpaid.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Brule, acting state executive director for the FSA, signed
the letter. He could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somewhere along the line human error occurred,'' said Larry
Mitchell, deputy administrator for FSA in Washington. ''We're still
investigating how that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said the farmers did not qualify in 1998 for funding
under a non-insurance assistance program and should not have been
granted funding under CLDAP. The farming requirement ''is the
policy of the program,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm outraged at the Department of Agriculture, quite
frankly,'' said U.S. Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-New Haven. ''Our oyster
farmers are not going to be punished for (the USDA's) mistakes. We
are going to exhaust every avenue to see that our farmers are not
devastated by the ineptitude of the Department of Agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLauro, who has contacted the USDA secretary, said the FSA
never spoke with farmers about alternate farming methods when
officials came soliciting applications for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''First of all, we think that's a misinterpretation of the
rule,'' said Backer of the FSA's farming restrictions. ''Can you
imagine looking out at Nebraska and seeing 200 acres of corn
planted in flower pots?''
</P>
<P>
   The same farming method is used on the Gulf Coast where about
two-thirds of the nation's oysters are farmed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very concerned about the challenges that are being
placed (in Connecticut) by the industry. It doesn't make sense,''
said Mike Vosin, president of the Molluskan Shellfish Institute,
which represents farmers, processors and distributors nationwide.
''I'm really appalled that this is happening in Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   Vosin, whose ancestors began farming in Louisiana after
immigrating from France in the 1700s, represents the seventh
generation to join the family business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Motivatit Seafood suffered great losses due to
Hurricane Andrew. Without the help of several million dollars in
federal disaster aid, the business may not have survived, said
Vosin.
</P>
<P>
   Vosin, who is also on the board of directors of the Gulf Oyster
Industry Council, which represents farmers from Florida to Texas,
said the industry must fight what is happening in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course we are going to, as an industry nationally, respond
through the congressional delegation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Backer, a Democratic state representative from Stratford, said
local farmers have a lawyer ready to fight the government's demand.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think there are a lot of basic tenants of law to go through
this process,'' he said. ''If we need to go to federal court, we
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Backer views the request as a contractual violation.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a promise. There was a contract. No one is disputing
the contract,'' he said. ''They had 90 days to catch this. It's
just horrendous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
