<HEADLINE> Deliberations continue for a third day in boy witness trial  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - The jury in the trial of a man accused
in the killings of an 8-year-old witness and the boy's mother
deliberated for a third day Wednesday without reaching a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler Jr., 28, is accused of arranging the murders of
8-year-old Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother, Karen Clarke,
to keep the boy from testifying against him in a 1998 murder case.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the jury heard court clerks read back testimony
from Peeler's former girlfriend, Angelina Keene, who said that
Peeler urged her to move away from the area about two months before
the Jan. 7, 1999, killings because ''witnesses are going to get
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury also heard the testimony of Kybarris Taylor, a friend
of Peeler's who said Peeler offered to pay him $10,000 to ''take
out two people'' for him about a month before the killings. Taylor
testified that Keene overheard Peeler's request, and that she also
urged him to do the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why don't you do that favor for him? His life is in danger,''
Keene said, according to Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   But Keene, under questioning from Peeler's defense lawyer,
testified that she didn't even know Taylor and had never overheard
Peeler ask anyone to kill two people.
</P>
<P>
   Since beginning its deliberations Monday afternoon, the jury has
reheard portions of testimony from 10 witnesses, including
Josephine Lee, the prosecution's star witness.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said she acted as a lookout while Peeler's brother, Adrian,
shot the mother and son to death in their home. She also said she
overheard Russell Peeler ask his brother to kill them the day
before the murders.
</P>
<P>
   But Russell Peeler's defense lawyers showed the jury letters Lee
wrote to her lawyer and former landlord in which she said she
didn't know anything about the murders and had lied to police about
the Peeler brothers' involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Peeler, who is accused of being the gunman, is scheduled
to be tried separately, after Russell Peeler's trial ends. Both
brothers face the possibility of the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
