<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
General Motors Corp. Class H shares, down $7.625 at $97.875
</P>
<P>
   GM said it will conduct a 3-for-1 split of the tracking stock
for its Hughes Electronics Corp. unit. The Class H shares represent
a dividend interest in Hughes, but not an ownership stake.
</P>
<P>
KLM Royal Dutch Airlines, up $2.25 at $28.75
</P>
<P>
   British Airways and KLM confirmed they have begun talks that
could lead to a merger. An alliance would create the world's
third-largest airline, behind United Airlines and American
Airlines. The combined airline would be valued at more than $7.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
Korea Telecom Corp., up $7.25 at $48.875
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors placed huge buy orders for shares in the
Korean telecommunications provider, Dow Jones Newswires reported.
</P>
<P>
Avon Products Inc., up 68.75 cents at $41.188
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said they are ''comfortable'' with analysts'
expectations of 51 cents a share for the second quarter. Avon said
it is ahead of its sales plan so far this year and expects to
exceed its financial goals for the year.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
MP3.com, up $5.25 at $16.875
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported the Internet music company is
close to a $15 to $20 million copyright-infringement settlement
with Warner Music Group. In April, MP3.com was found liable for
copyright infringement and is now negotiating with several record
labels.
</P>
<P>
Block Drug Co., up $12.50 at $39.875
</P>
<P>
   The company, a maker of denture care and oral health care
products, has hired Goldman Sachs to help it review strategic
options for boosting shareholder value. Also, Block said profits
rose 10.6 percent in its fiscal fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
Applied Micro Circuits Corp., down $9.938 at $96.875
</P>
<P>
   The maker of chips for telecommunications equipment is expected
to see slower growth in sales to its biggest customer, Nortel
Networks Corp. Applied Micro warned analysts of the decline in
Nortel business at the Supercomm conference in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Intervoice-Brite Inc., down $7.438 at $6.125
</P>
<P>
   The company said it expects to report a first-quarter loss of 3
cents to 5 cents a share for fiscal 2001. Analysts had anticipated
earnings of 25 cents. Intervoice-Brite makes call automation
systems.
</P>
