<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Pro-Israel Militiamen Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
By SAM F. GHATTAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- A military court on Wednesday found
another 24 former pro-Israeli militiamen guilty of collaboration
and sentenced most of them to one year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The former members of the now-defunct South Lebanon Army were
convicted as the country debated sentences handed down earlier in
the week against ex-SLA fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The 24 appeared before the Military Tribunal in Beirut, the
second group to go on trial since the May 24 Israeli withdrawal
from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The former militiamen were charged with collaborating with the
enemy, joining the militia or entering Israel, a country still
technically at war with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the military judges sentenced 16 of the 24
militiamen to jail for one year. Three others were sentenced to 18
months in prison. Two each received a two-year sentence and three
got three years each.
</P>
<P>
   The court, whose verdicts cannot be appealed, also fined 22 of
the militiamen $270 each.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent response to guerrilla warnings that revenge could
be exacted, court officials said the tribunal also ruled that some
convicts were forbidden from returning to their hometowns for up to
five years after serving their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Some 1,500 SLA members surrendered to Lebanese authorities
before and after the Israeli pullout, while about 7,000 Lebanese --
ex-militiamen and their families -- sought refuge in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the court tried and sentenced 77 former SLA fighters.
Forty-eight of them received a one-year prison term; the heaviest
sentence was five years.
</P>
<P>
   The sentences were seen as lenient by anti-Israeli guerrillas
and their supporters and harsh by relatives of the condemned and
some politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, the main guerrilla group that fought the Israelis in
the occupied zone, has demanded tough sentences. Its leaders have
also warned that any freed ex-militiamen will not be safe in their
villages.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing Christian politician Dory Chamoun -- whose late
father, ex-president Camille Chamoun, was among Christian leaders
who welcomed the Israelis during their 1982 invasion of Lebanon --
demanded an SLA amnesty similar to a 1991 pardon that covered
militiamen who committed crimes during the 1975-90 civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ''It happened before that Lebanese collaborated with
Palestinians against the state. Others cooperated with the Syrians
when they were shelling residential areas, and they received an
amnesty,'' he was quoted as saying in Wednesday's An-Nahar
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He said an amnesty would encourage people who fled to Israel to
return home.
</P>
<P>
   Some Lebanese joined the SLA voluntarily, but others served to
earn a living in the economically depressed border zone or were
recruited under the threat of imprisonment or expulsion of their
families.
</P>
<P>
   The militia, which was paid and armed by Israel, helped the
Israeli army for 18 years control the self-proclaimed security zone
in south Lebanon. The militiamen also controlled the lives of
120,000 people, jailing and expelling hundreds who were deemed a
security threat to them and the occupation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
