<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Syphilis Outbreak Contained  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A syphilis outbreak primarily among gay men
in Los Angeles County has been contained, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   No new cases were reported since the first week of April, said
Diane Goodwin, spokeswoman for the county Department of Health
Services. The outbreak raised fears that HIV might spread at a
faster rate than usual.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of the new syphilis patients was 36, which
surprised authorities because that age group is considered to be
informed about preventing sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The county responded with a $560,000 campaign of condom
distribution, syphilis testing and precautionary advertisements
targeting the gay community, although officials noted the outbreak
also affected heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-three syphilis cases were reported between January and
late March, compared with the usual 100 in a year, Goodwin said. Of
the new cases, 53 were HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   Syphilis, curable with antibiotics, is transmitted through
sexual intercourse or oral sex and is characterized by a lesion in
the mouth or on sexual organs, or a body rash, sometimes with a
fever and sore throat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
