<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Race themes permeate Assembly debate, suggesting a divided New Jersey </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A divided New Jersey met - and fought - on
the Assembly floor this week.
</P>
<P>
   On one side were the wealthy suburbs filled with a lot of white
people. On the other side were the decaying cities, filled with
mostly minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Are these two separate New Jerseys, fighting it out for scarce
resources? Or is it politics?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a little of both.
</P>
<P>
   During debates Monday on various issues - school construction,
the census, paid police leave - several Assembly Democrats charged
that Republican measures were racist, discriminatory and
mean-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were unsuccessful in defeating any bill, they came
close.
</P>
<P>
   The school construction legislation, which would create the
largest school building program in state history, passed by only a
41-29 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican bill would force the state to use only an
actual census head count, rather than statistical sampling, when
redrawing legislative districts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and other opponents charged the method leaves
minorities, recent immigrants and city residents undercounted and
therefore underrepresented in government.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's not racism, it certainly seems to be,'' Assemblyman
William Payne, D-Essex, said during Monday's debate.
</P>
<P>
   A bill that would allow certain police officers paid leave to
attend conferences also drew charges of racism because it failed to
include minority police groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans say some Democrats are too quick to introduce
race into the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some members feel it's unfortunate that when there are policy
debates and differences of opinion on policy issues, that some
members of the Democratic caucus are quick to play the race card,''
said Chuck Leitgeb, spokesman for the Assembly Republicans. ''It
has nothing to do with race.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Guy Gregg, R-Morris, who sponsored the census bill,
said some Democrats are angling for a reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think, unfortunately, over the years, (racist) has become a
term that has been thrown around to strike a chord, with the
expectation of striking fear in the other side,'' said Gregg, who
is white.
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats say it's important to discuss race - even if
it makes people uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ''So, we shouldn't debate or question the motives behind people
who are apparently trying to diminish the power of the minority
vote?'' said Payne. ''If it's a sore that's festering, let's bring
it out into the open. If we're wrong, that's fine. But let's
discuss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Herb Conaway, D-Burlington, who is black, agreed
that lawmakers, white and black, should address the issue of race -
when the issue merits it.
</P>
<P>
   But he also wondered whether it was appropriate in every
instance Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the school construction measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly version of the bill gives lawmakers the power to
oversee construction in any district that receives 100 percent
state funding, which could be as many as 114 districts, including
30 ''special needs'' districts.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, some Democrats said the provision
discriminates against those 30 poor, mostly urban districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just the (special needs) districts that were affected
by this oversight,'' he said. ''Certainly, when you look at those
100-plus districts that this provision would affect, they're not
all districts serving the needs of poor and/or minority children.''
</P>
<P>
   But a bill that would provide paid leave for police officers to
attend conferences left out minority groups, Conaway added.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is interesting to note that there were no paternal police
organizations of color included in that bill, but Italians were,''
Conaway said. ''Why isn't every group included?''
</P>
<P>
   Because the bill included only groups that had asked bill
sponsor Assemblyman Nicholas Asselta, R-Cumberland, for help,
Asselta said. He also told minority members that he would
co-sponsor another bill including minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''After my answers to Assemblyman Payne, they were comfortable
because they voted for the bill,'' Asselta said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Strickland, director of the Garden State Coalition of
Schools, which represents wealthier districts, said introducing
race into the school construction program could be damaging.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you take a look at the school construction bill as a whole,
lawmakers are dealing with all the issues - urban and suburban - at
a historic level,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the past 10 years, urbans and suburbans have worked
really productively together,'' she added. ''Side efforts that
might dismantle this really wholesome step forward are dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-07-00 1830 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor meets with police incident victims  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki hugged the mother of New
York City police shooting victim Patrick Dorismond and said he was
sorry for the family's loss, according to witnesses at their
meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki met Monday night for almost 45 minutes with more than a
dozen relatives of shootings, beatings and other incidents
involving police officers from New York City, according to state
Assemblyman Keith Wright, who also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''He hugged the Dorismond family, which I thought was a good act
of symbolism,'' Wright, a Manhattan Democrat, said. ''He did agree
to start a dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Daily News, which first reported the governor's
meeting with the families, also said Pataki told Marie Dorismond,
''All New Yorkers owe you an apology and our efforts to make sure
it doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki spokeswoman Zenia Mucha said the governor ''was
apologizing for their losses'' and made no apology for the official
actions of police or other agencies in the incidents which caused
the families' relatives to be hurt or killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not his place,'' Mucha said. ''He went in there to give
them an opportunity to have their say. As with any other situation,
he said we need to learn and there are always ways to look at a
situation and figure out ways that it can be made better.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani received much criticism
from minority groups for refusing to meet with the Dorismond family
or to apologize for some incidents of police violence.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday outside City Hall about the governor's actions,
Giuliani said, ''I think it's perfectly appropriate for him to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ''And what I said before is that I have expressed my feelings
about that a couple of weeks ago and have also attempted to meet
with the (Dorismond) family twice,'' Giuliani said. ''I'm still
happy to do that, except they wanted a lawyer present.''
</P>
<P>
   That attorney is Johnnie Cochran, who is representing the
Dorismonds in their $100 million civil claim against the city.
</P>
<P>
   Once the grand jury decides if the Dorismond shooting involved
criminal behavior, Giuliani said he would like to try again to
reach out to the Dorismond family.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Dorismond was shot and killed in March by police
involved in a buy-and-bust operation in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Others at the state Capitol meeting were relatives or
representatives of Amadou Diallo, Anthony Baez, Gary Busch, Anthony
Rosario, Hilton Vega, Malcolm Ferguson and Yong Xin Huang - all
killed or injured at the hands of police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said the relatives, in Albany to help promote bills
sponsors said would make some police officers more sensitive and
less violence-prone, met for about 45 minutes with state Criminal
Justice Coordinator Katherine Lapp Monday. Pataki dropped by,
saying he could stay for only five minutes, but remained for nearly
45 minutes, Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it was an excellent first step,'' Wright said. ''The
families are somewhat frustrated by the process in Albany.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Pataki said of Monday's meeting and the losses
suffered by the families, ''We can't just say it's unfortunate. We
have to look at what happened and learn from it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
