<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutor accuses owner of clinic of a massive fraud  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A prosecutor during opening statements Wednesday
accused the owner of a Manhattan cosmetic surgery clinic where a
liposuction patient once died of leading a massive fraud to cheat
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert C. Juman said Sonia Lafontaine
submitted nearly a half million dollars in bogus claims so cosmetic
surgery, which is not usually covered by insurance companies, would
be paid for anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Juman said some clients of the Lafontaine-Rish Medical
Association on 57th Street were told to lie to obtain free service
for procedures that could result in fuller lips and slimmer hips.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of these people had no idea a fraud was being
committed,'' Juman said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor accused Lafontaine of performing medical
procedures herself, including removing lesions and unsightly veins,
even though she was not a doctor. He also said she convinced others
to submit insurance forms for procedures that were exaggerated or
never performed.
</P>
<P>
   But her lawyer, Myles Malman, said his client was ''victimized
and betrayed'' by her husband, Arthur Kissel, who remains a
fugitive in the case, and a doctor, Benito Rish, who served as her
mentor and friend for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rish pleaded guilty to insurance fraud in March and is awaiting
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   ''She sits here alone at that table,'' Malman said of a client
who dabbed tears from her eyes shortly before opening statements
began.
</P>
<P>
   ''What this case is really about is a woman, 46 years old, who's
been working a long time very, very hard. She wanted everyone to be
beautiful healthy, medically healthy, spiritually healthy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Lafontaine opened clinics in Canada in the 1980s that
were so successful that she started selling her own line of beauty
products.
</P>
<P>
   He said she decided in 1990 to open a clinic in Manhattan along
with a man she had met and married within several months and a
doctor who had taught her much of what she knew about the cosmetic
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ms. Lafontaine was the victim of these two men in this
horrible situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, the clinic was under investigation by insurance
companies and the federal goverment. In January 1998, an overweight
Jersey City, N.J., man who wanted to be a police officer died of
complications due to anesthesia. The anesthesiologist later
surrendered her license to practice medicine.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Lafontaine faces up to five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
