<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani reaches out ... tentatively  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - When he quit the U.S. Senate race last month,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani pledged to make an effort to reach out to
communities that complained about being overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has met with a handful of elected officials
largely ignored in the past, but has yet to visit neighborhoods
like Harlem and the South Bronx that feel particularly neglected.
</P>
<P>
   And because Giuliani has made similar promises before, his
resolve has been greeted with skepticism in some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has had chats with people before, and afterward, there was
a deterioration in those relationships,'' said the Rev. Calvin
Butts, pastor of the influential Abyssinian Baptist Church in
Harlem and a frequent critic of the mayor. ''He's got to go out to
the communities, and even then, there will always be the question
of whether it is sincere or being done for political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has acknowledged that he is unsure of how to begin
healing the divide between City Hall and large segments of the
city's black and Latino communities.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent remarks, he is clearly feeling his way for a path
that is at once conciliatory, but does not betray his core beliefs
or alienate his largely white political base.
</P>
<P>
   During a television interview last month, the mayor acknowledged
his indecision.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know. I don't know,'' he said about reaching out.
''There are people that feel that I don't take them into equal
consideration. And I always tried to deal with that with objective
facts, I always tried to deal with that by showing, 'Well, you
know, how can you say that? I've done as much for you as I have for
anyone else. I've done more in some cases.'''
</P>
<P>
   ''But maybe there's a different form of communication that I
have to learn,'' he added. ''I have to make people get to see the
real me, what I'm trying to do, what I'm trying to accomplish, and
break down some of the barriers that I've created.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's critics say he first must institute a series of
reforms, including civilian oversight of the police department and
greater attention to health care and housing needs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously it's not enough just to meet with elected
officials,'' said former Mayor David Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   One meeting the mayor has not yet held is with the family of
Patrick Dorismond, an unarmed black man gunned down by police in
March. After the shooting, Giuliani released Dorismond's juvenile
record and suggested the victim had caused his own death.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani has steadfastly refused to offer the family his
condolences, he acknowledged last month that he should have tried
to be more ''human'' in his comments.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose again this week after Gov. George Pataki
apologized to the Dorismonds for their loss - an action the mayor
has said he will not take for now because the Dorismond family
wants attorney Johnnie Cochran, who is representing the family in
its $100 million civil claim against the city, to be present during
a meeting with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mayor was looking for a heart-to-heart, not something with
lawyers,'' said Giuliani spokeswoman Sunny Mindel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, during the past two weeks, Giuliani has met with
Comptroller Alan Hevesi and Public Advocate Mark Green and has a
meeting scheduled Thursday with Manhattan Borough President C.
Virginia Fields, the city's highest-ranking black elected office
holder.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's meeting with Green, the city's second-ranking
elected official, was the first in four years. It lasted about five
minutes. And though the two have traded verbal firebombs for years,
Green said the meeting was cordial.
</P>
<P>
   ''We agreed to have a better relationship on the issues we agree
on,'' said Green, who said topics included high technology and
health policy.
</P>
<P>
   Green remains unconvinced that the mayor is committed to change.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope this is an era of new feeling but 99 percent of the
time he's had a government by enemies list and has treated any good
faith criticism as a beast to be eliminated. And that hurt the
city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Giuliani met with Bronx Borough President Fernando
Ferrer - for just the second time since Giuliani was elected in
1993 and for the first time in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the hour-long meeting was too little, too late, Ferrer
responded, ''It's never too late, its never too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Butts however, is of a different mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me, I think it's best, as they say in the black church, to
turn him over to the Lord,'' said Butts.
</P>
<P>
   Translation? ''I'm through with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
