<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney: Second man to plead guilty in killing of rabbi's wife  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Because he wants to ensure that ''the truth
comes out,'' the second of two men who say they were hired by a
Cherry Hill rabbi to kill his wife will plead guilty Thursday, his
attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul M. Daniels, 27, of Pennsauken, will admit to the Nov. 1,
1994, killing of Carol Neulander, Daniels' lawyer, Craig Mitnick,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels will plead guilty to aggravated manslaughter and
robbery, Mitnick said. His alleged accomplice, Leonard Jenoff,
pleaded guilty to aggravated manslaughter June 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's in his best interest to do this,'' Mitnick said, adding
that his client already has confessed to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick said Daniels wants to take responsibility for his part
in the killing, but also ''wants to make sure the rabbi takes
responsibility for what he believes the rabbi's role in this was.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He wants to make sure the truth comes out,'' Mitnick said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, 54, of Collingswood, admitted in court last week that he
hit Carol Neulander in the back of the head with a lead pipe in her
Cherry Hill home. He has said the Rabbi Fred Neulander agreed to
pay $30,000 for the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Camden County Assistant Prosecutor James P. Lynch has said
Daniels was ''the primary actor in striking the blows.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mitnick said Daniels, ''a paranoid schizophrenic and a very
weak human being,'' was coerced into taking part in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was manipulated by both Jenoff and the rabbi - Jenoff,
directly, and the rabbi, indirectly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, 58, who founded Congregation M'Kor Shalom synagogue
with his wife in 1974, allegedly wanted her killed so he could
continue having an affair with Philadelphia radio personality
Elaine Soncini.
</P>
<P>
   He believed a divorce would jeopardize his position as senior
rabbi at the synagogue. He resigned three months after the killing,
however, after reports surfaced about two extramarital affairs he'd
allegedly had with members of his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, who was charged in the killing in 1998, maintains his
innocence. He faces charges of accomplice murder and conspiracy to
commit murder.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels was to appear before Superior Court Judge Linda
Rosenzweig Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for Neulander's trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
