<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Boosts Utah Preservation Bill  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bill aimed at preserving Utah territory made
famous as a hide-out for outlaws Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid
grew stronger Wednesday as House Democrats pushed through an
amendment expanding the area.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would create a 1.3 million national conservation
area in the San Rafael Swell, a dramatic sandstone uplift 35 miles
wide and 85 miles long in the desert of southeastern Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the original measure did not go far enough to
restrict off-road vehicle use and could have undermined wilderness
protection for the entire area.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats won approval of an amendment enlarging the
conservation area from under 1 million acres to nearly 1.3 million
acres. The measure also would ban mining in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The House did not immediately vote on the measure after
approving the amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the original measure, including Utah's Republican
congressional delegation and Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, say
it was a compromise to protect a natural jewel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Members are hearing from the extreme environmental groups that
this is anti-wilderness legislation or some other untruths like
that,'' said Rep. Jim Hansen, R-Utah. ''Apparently some of these
extremist groups would rather raise money than protect land.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents included the Southern Utah Wilderness Alliance and the
Sierra Club, which sent e-mails to members asking them to urge
their representatives to kill the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill is anti-wilderness because it would continue the
abuse of this land, and its arbitrary boundaries would divide or
exclude some wilderness-quality areas,'' said Rep. Maurice Hinchey,
D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress has not designated any of the area as
wilderness, the Bureau of Land Management manages about half of the
proposed conservation area under wilderness guidelines, said Rep.
Mark Udall, D-Colo. Those rules ban nearly all activity other than
hiking or horseback riding, including mining, vehicle or bicycle
use or building any structures.
</P>
<P>
   The House agreed -- by a one-vote margin, 212-211 -- to require
the BLM to manage the land at least as restrictively as it does
now.
</P>
<P>
   The swell, a kidney-shaped bulge on what used to be an ocean
floor, is so rugged and remote that Cassidy and his infamous Hole
in the Wall gang used it as a hide-out after robbing miners in the
late 1800s. The desert in and around the swell has become a popular
area for off-road vehicle users as well as hikers, kayakers and
rafters.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would create a national conservation area to preserve
the swell and adjoining areas called Factory Butte and Muddy Creek.
It also would declare 2.8 million-acre Emery County, which
encompasses most of the swell, as a ''Western legacy district.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure would provide up to $1 million a year for a decade
in federal money to help promote tourism and protect historic sites
in the county.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would give the BLM four years to develop a management
plan for the conservation area, which opponents say gives off-road
vehicle users time to wear new trails into the land and further
damage it. The management plan would have to be developed with
input from local officials, off-road and other recreational users,
environmentalists and the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://utahreach.usu.edu/emery/heritage/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
