<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court papers show prosecutors leaning on Brooklyn terrorism suspect </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Prosecutors tried to compel an Algerian arrested
in Brooklyn to cooperate against his alleged co-conspirators in a
plot to sneak explosives from Canada into the United States, court
papers released by prosecutors Wednesday show.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers detailing the case against Abdel Ghani Meskini were
released by U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White after they were filed in
Montreal in an effort to extradite Mokhtar Haouari for a trial in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   A message left with a lawyer for Meskini was not immediately
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari, an Algerian, is accused of playing a central role in a
terrorism plot that resulted in the December capture of Ahmed
Ressam, another Algerian, as he crossed the border from Canada into
Port Angeles, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   An inspection of Ressam's car after it rolled off a ferry boat
revealed explosives and timing devices with Ressam's fingerprints
on them hidden beneath a mat covering the vehicle's spare tire
well, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   A slip of paper found on Ressam contained Meskini's telephone
numbers, leading authorities to his Brooklyn residence, where they
arrested him.
</P>
<P>
   After the arrest, Meskini provided investigators an extensive
statement corroborated by other evidence in the case, including
telephone records, the government said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   ''While Meskini has not agreed to be a witness against Haouari,
that does not preclude the use of Meskini's statement against
Haouari,'' prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The government said in the court papers that it was prepared to
try to force Meskini to testify against Haouari, even offering him
limited immunity so that his testimony would not be used against
him at his own trial.
</P>
<P>
   It noted that Meskini after his arrest had tried to make several
consensually recorded telephone calls to Haouari at the direction
of arresting officers but had been unsuccessful at getting a
response.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, someone picked up the telephone, telling Meskini
that Haouari was not at home and that he should not call again
because the phone was tapped, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, 32, has pleaded innocent to nine charges including
possessing and transporting explosives with the intent to cause
damage or injury.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari and Meskini are accused of conspiring since October 1997
to support members and associates of a terrorist group. They are
also accused of conspiring to transfer fake or stolen U.S.
immigration identity cards and passports of other countries and of
using fake credit and bank cards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
