<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 77; Nasdaq Is Up 83  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks closed higher Wednesday after
a Goldman Sachs analyst predicted IBM would have a strong year. The
rosy prospects for IBM helped pull investors off the sidelines,
where they had been fitfully awaiting a judge's ruling on
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stocks came on very strongly once they found a catalyst,''
said Scott Bleier, chief investment strategist at Prime Charter
Ltd. in New York. ''It wasn't anything terribly dramatic, but
there's a lot of money on the sidelines, and a fervent desire to
get it to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 77.29 to 10,812.86, while
the Nasdaq composite index rose 82.89 to 3,839.26. Both indexes
recovered from early declines.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators were also higher; the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
rose 13.52 to 1,471.36.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market seems to be on the path of least resistance, and
that is to the upside,'' said Bleier, noting that investors are
continuing to buy stocks even after solid gains last week that
could have set up a big bout of profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks continued a steady recovery from their swoon in
March and April, led by IBM, which rose $8.875 to $121.25.
Well-known Goldman Sachs analyst Laura Conigliaro said orders were
strong in the past two months, and she said investors may be
undervaluing the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology companies also fared better. Microstrategy, a
software maker that has struggled since admitting it would have to
restate earnings for the past few years, rose $9.625 to $37.625 as
investors anticipated that the company may soon receive financing
from an outside source.
</P>
<P>
   And biotechnology stocks continued their most winning streak.
Immunex rose $4.204 to $36.313 after the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration expanded its approval of the company's Enbrel
rheumatoid arthritis drug to more patients.
</P>
<P>
   The good news from a diverse range of technology companies
helped distract investors from their concerns over Microsoft. After
the close of trading, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
issued his order to split the computer software company into two
separate businesses. Microsoft chairman Bill Gates vowed to appeal
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose 87.5 cents to $70.50 during the regular session,
then rose to $72 per share after the decision was released.
</P>
<P>
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines rose $2.25 to $28.75. KLM and British
Airways confirmed they have begun talks that could lead to a
merger. An alliance would create the world's third-largest airline,
behind United Airlines and American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways edged up 37.5 cents to $59.938.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, trading was quiet. Analysts said interest rate
worries, which eased last week amid a slew of reports that signaled
a modest economic slowdown, haven't truly left the market. Many
investors are waiting for more information as they try to discern
whether the Fed may finally be finished raising interest rates to
cool the pace of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Federal Reserve Governor Laurence Meyer said the Fed
may have to force U.S. economic growth to a more substantial
slowdown. But he said he believes the slowdown can take place
without derailing the economy's expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Several considerations provide optimism that the outcome will
be a benign one -- a soft landing as opposed to a hard landing,''
Meyer told the Boston Economics Club.
</P>
<P>
   The next crucial piece of data for Fed economists and investors
will be the Producer Price Index, due out Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 1.02
billion shares, compared with 1.13 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.89 to 516.54.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 2.1 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 0.9 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
fell 0.7 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 1.4 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
