<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Still Presses Finance Reform  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain, who sought the White House
on a platform of campaign finance reform, pressed the Senate on
Wednesday to require a secretive new generation of political groups
to disclose their donors.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is (a) dark, uncontrolled sector of the political
landscape,'' McCain, R-Ariz., said in remarks on the Senate floor.
''It a danger to our electoral system.''
</P>
<P>
   Under his proposal, nonprofit groups that engage in
campaign-style activity would be required to disclose both their
donors and their expenditures. Currently, there is no disclosure
requirement on these groups, nor are there limits on the donations
they can accept.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's proposal came in the form of an amendment to an
unrelated bill that deals with the military, and a vote was set for
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first time since his White House campaign ended
that the Arizona Republican brought his signature issue to the
floor of the Senate, although he did so in a far more modest form
than previous comprehensive proposals that included a ban on
so-called soft-money.
</P>
<P>
   Those earlier efforts have ended in gridlock, with McCain and
his allies, principally Democrats, unable to gain the 60 votes
needed to overcome a filibuster backed by the GOP leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, McCain cited comments made in the past by
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss, and other critics to the effect
that disclosure that they favor disclosure of political donations,
as a means of guarding against scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment was designed to force disclosure on so-called 527s
-- groups named after section 527 of the tax code -- created in 1974
for political groups to enjoy certain tax advantages without
publicly disclosing anything about themselves. These groups fall
outside the purview of federal election law by declaring that they
engage in issues, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   To operate legally, they cannot coordinate their activities with
candidates who benefit from their ads, and all sides insist there
is no communication between them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they are beginning to play an increasingly
prominent role in politics. One group ran ads favorable to Texas
Gov. George W. Bush at a time when McCain was still challenging for
the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Democrats have filed a lawsuit against the GOP
whip, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, alleging that he illegally oversees
the operation of several 527s.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's attempt to inject campaign finance issues into the
defense bill was seconded by Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., who
said the two men would soon propose a separate amendment to ban
so-called soft money.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Democrats led by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., indicated they would seek a vote on Thursday on yet
another issue unrelated to the military -- a proposal to strengthen
the hand of patients dealing with their HMOs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 2008 </TRAILER>
