<HEADLINE> GOP Accuses HUD of Wasteful Spending  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans moved Wednesday to cut $2.5
billion from President Clinton's proposed budget next year for the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, accusing the agency of
wasting nearly $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee approved a $30 billion budget
next year for HUD, $2.5 billion less than Clinton sought. The
action was taken on a broad $101 billion spending bill that also
would fund the Department of Veterans Affairs, NASA and other
agencies. The full House could take up the bill as early as next
week.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not tolerate having Americans' hard-earned money
frittered away on ineffective policies and mismanaged projects,''
Rep. Mark Green, R-Wis., said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas said that when
Republicans were insisting on budget cuts a year ago, ''We heard
from all of these agencies, 'Oh we can't afford that. That's
squeezing our turnip too tight. There's not enough blood left.' Yet
we found these examples of this waste and inefficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to congressional leaders, White House budget chief
Jack Lew warned that administration officials would urge Clinton to
veto the bill. He cited its reductions from the president's
proposals for housing, the environment, space and science, as well
as its proposed elimination of the Americorps community service
program, a Clinton favorite.
</P>
<P>
   HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo said the cuts were ''an attack on the
poorest and most vulnerable families in America,'' saying they
would eliminate plans to provide 120,000 poor families with new
rental assistance vouchers and $30 million for reclaiming polluted
urban ''brownfields.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., a leading Republican on housing issues
who is also running against Hillary Rodham Clinton for a Senate
seat, said in a statement: ''We continue to be presented with
evidence that shows ... taxpayer dollars being wasted by HUD.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are simply raising questions with an agency that
consistently fails to manage itself in a manner that taxpayers
deserve,'' said Lazio, who chairs a banking subcommittee on
housing.
</P>
<P>
   HUD has long been a favorite target of suspicion by some
Republicans in Congress, who see it as an example of big, inept and
wasteful government. Several years ago, HUD was labeled
''high-risk'' by auditors at the General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's allegations consisted mostly of details released in
earlier congressional hearings or reports by HUD's inspector
general.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was an inspector general's report last year which
found $935 million in subsidy overpayments in HUD's assisted living
programs. Another report found ''little if any'' measurable
evidence that $8.5 million spent on HUD's new ''storefront
operations'' has benefited HUD customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 2018 </TRAILER>
