<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect Denies bin Laden Link  </HEADLINE>
By SHAFIKA MATTAR
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- The leading defendant in a terrorism trial
told the court Wednesday he had no links to the Saudi militant
Osama bin Laden and that police had obtained his confession through
torture.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the defense case, Khader Abu Hosher, 36, told the State
Security Court his interrogators had hung him upside down and
beaten him severely.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Hosher is the alleged leader of 28 men on trial in the State
Security Court for belonging to an outlawed group that conspired to
carry out terrorist attacks on American and Israeli tourists in
Jordan. They are also charged with illegal possession of explosives
and firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen of the accused are in police custody. The remaining 12
are outside Jordan and are being tried in absentia.
</P>
<P>
   All 28 are suspected of having links with bin Laden, a
Saudi-born millionaire who is wanted in the United States for
allegedly plotting the 1998 bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania. The bombings claimed 244 lives.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment sheet does not identify the outlawed group, but
the military prosecutor, Lt. Col. Mahmoud Obeidat, has told
reporters the suspects were linked to al-Qaeda -- or ''the base'' --
a terrorist organization allegedly led by bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Obeidat and other officials say the accused planned to attack
U.S. and Israeli tourists during New Year's celebrations at Mount
Nebo -- where tradition says Moses saw the Promised Land -- and a
Christian settlement along the Jordan River said to be the site
where Jesus was baptized.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never seen or met Osama bin Laden,'' Abu Hosher told
the court Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ten other defendants also read out statements to the court,
denying the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was adjourned until June 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
