<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal regulators allow to psychiatric hospital remain open  </HEADLINE>
ngfonflspr
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Conn. (AP) - Citing improving conditions, federal
regulators on Wednesday decided not to cut off funding to a
psychiatric hospital where two patients died in less than two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Health Care Financing Administration ''rescinded the
termination track'' of St. Francis Care Behavioral Health hospital,
said David Banks, special assistant to the regional director of
HCFA.
</P>
<P>
   The ''termination track'' could have led the loss of Medicare
and Medicaid funding. St. Francis Care , formerly Elmcrest
Hospital, was placed on the termination list following the January
death of a 30-year-old female patient.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Beninato died after being overmedicated. She had taken a
mix of 12 different tranquilizers, anti-anxiety drugs and muscle
relaxers.
</P>
<P>
   State investigators found hospital workers failed to develop an
adequate treatment plan for Beninato and then failed to properly
monitor her condition.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Benianto's death, St. Francis Care announced that
it had fired two top-ranking hospital administrators, made other
administrative changes and submitted a plan of correction to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   St. Francis also agreed to a state consent decree calling for
the oversight of an independent monitor. As part of that decree,
St. Francis agreed to pay $125,000 to a state drug abuse prevention
program.
</P>
<P>
   ''We appreciate the fact that the Health Care Financing
Administration has recognized the considerable strides that have
been made and our commitment to providing high quality,
compassionate behavioral health services while ensuring the safety
and well-being of the patients entrusted to our care,'' said Dr.
Edward S. Johnson, a hospital spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   HCFA will also be permitted to inspect the hospital at any time
during the next year, Banks said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is similar to a consent decree signed by St.
Francis and state regulators two years ago. That agreement was
reached after Andrew McClain, an 11-year-old state foster child,
died of suffocation after a mental health aide put him in a
restraint hold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
