<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former CBS news executive Blair Clark dies in Princeton  </HEADLINE>
By NINA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Blair Clark, a former CBS news executive
who also managed Eugene McCarthy's presidential campaign, died
Tuesday. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   He died at Princeton Medical Center after complications from
colon surgery, according to his son Timothy Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Easthampton, N.Y., Clark was raised in Princeton, heir
to the Clark Thread fortune. His father, William, was a federal
judge in Newark and a friend of President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Like Roosevelt, Clark considered himself a traitor to his class,
his son said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He came from a conservative background, but through his own
force of intellect he became a true liberal,'' Timothy Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was close friends with the late poet Robert Lowell, a prep
school friend who dedicated a book to him, and President John F.
Kennedy, a Harvard University classmate.
</P>
<P>
   While at Harvard, Clark served as editor of the Harvard Crimson
and enlisted Kennedy to work on the college paper, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark began his career in journalism as a reporter for the St.
Louis Post-Dispatch, then spent five years in the U.S. Army during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, he took $60,000 he inherited from his grandmother and
founded The New Hampshire Sunday News. His star reporter was Ben
Bradlee, who is now vice president of The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was really bright and thoughtful,'' Bradlee said. ''He
thought about the role of newspapers, the role of television. He
played an important role by being good at what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark worked for the Boston Herald and Traveler before joining
CBS News as a foreign correspondent in Paris in 1953. He came
stateside in 1956 to cover the presidential campaign and then
anchor ''The World Tonight'' for CBS Radio Network.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, Kennedy offered to make Clark ambassador to Morocco,
but he became vice president and general manager of CBS News
instead, according to Kaiser's book.
</P>
<P>
   While Clark was in that position, CBS hired reporters Mike
Wallace, Morley Safer and Dan Rather. The news broadcast was
expanded from 15 minutes to a half hour - a first for network
television. In addition, Walter Cronkite was appointed to succeed
Douglas Edwards as anchor of ''The Evening News.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a time when television news was being invented. There
was a lot of disagreement within the hierarchy about how the job
should be done,'' Cronkite said, adding that professional
disagreements with Clark never interfered with their longtime
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ''Blair brought a high sense of news integrity to the news
business. He made some people uncomfortable - those who were
inclined to sensationalize,'' Cronkite said.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint as associate publisher of the New York Post, Clark
became the campaign manager for Democratic presidential candidate
Eugene McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's role in the campaign was part of Charles Kaiser's book
''1968 in America'', which focused on McCarthy's presidential bid
and the anti-war movement.
</P>
<P>
   Clark worked as a freelance writer from 1969-75. He was the
editor of The Nation magazine from 1976-78. He also conducted a
seminar on the press and politics at Princeton University in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., said Clark never lost
his zeal. Three weeks ago, Clark proposed that Moynihan help him
preserve the Manhattan townhouse that once belonged to Roosevelt by
endowing it to Hunter College.
</P>
<P>
   ''Blair Clark was a member of that great generation of American
journalists who saw the onset of the Cold War and reported it for a
generation,'' said Moynihan. ''He was a man of perfect honor and
beautiful character.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark had two sons, Timothy and Cameron, with the late Jessie
Holladay Philbin. The couple divorced in 1960. Cameron died in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Timothy, Clark is survived by his second wife, Joanna
Rostropowicz, their son, Ian Clark, and a stepson, Tomasz
Malinowski; a sister, Anne Martindell; and a brother, William
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete Wednesday. Kimble Funeral
Home of Princeton is handling the arrangements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-07-00 2106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
