<HEADLINE> Lazio attacks HUD, says he and Congress have reformed housing  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Rep. Rick Lazio said Wednesday that Congress,
not the Clinton administration's Department of Housing and Urban
Development, has led the charge on housing reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's attack - the second on HUD in two days - came as
Congressional Republicans detailed what they said was fraud and
waste at the agency under Andrew Cuomo, a backer of Lazio's Senate
rival Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   HUD officials fired back Wednesday, saying Lazio has been
ineffective in his role as chairman of the Subcommittee on Housing.
</P>
<P>
   ''As for Mr. Lazio, he has distinguished himself as the chairman
of the committee that has never enacted housing legislation,'' HUD
spokesman David Egner said. HUD officials said while Lazio has been
successful at attaching his initiatives to spending bills, he has
been unable to get significant legislation passed through his
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio never mentioned Cuomo by name but the two New Yorkers have
sparred over housing policy in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Wednesday that ''Congress has been able to able to
enact major housing and community development reform legislation,
oftentimes in spite of opposition from the Clinton-Gore
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are simply raising questions with an agency that
consistently fails to manage itself in a manner that taxpayers
deserve,'' the Republican lawmaker said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio camp late Wednesday said Egner's assertion was untrue
and pointed, for example, to a bill the congressman helped pass
this year smoothing over obstacles to home ownership and helping
teachers purchase homes in the districts where they work. Egner
countered that the legislation has yet to be passed in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio used his attack Wednesday as another opportunity to tout a
laundry list of his own housing initiatives, including a 1998
overhaul of public housing that put in place work requirements for
many tenants as well as his efforts to make affordable housing
available to senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Housing was also the focus of a speech Lazio made Tuesday to the
New York Conference of Mayors in Saratoga Springs, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans, including House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, on Wednesday said HUD had wasted almost $1 billion even as
the agencies own literature showed that millions of people were
suffering from housing needs.
</P>
<P>
   Egner called the GOP's complaints ''a transparent attempt to
divert attention from the Republican budget cutting knife which
today is poised to carve $2.1 billion from HUD.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey praised Lazio at the Capitol Hill event, even though the
Long Island lawmaker could not attend because of a scheduling
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ''The work that Rick has done on public housing I think has done
so much to make these housing organizations more effective in the
lives of real people. It's one of the areas that I would celebrate
as great legislative service from the heart,'' the Texas Republican
said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   www.hud.gov
</P>
<P>
   www.lazio2000.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
