<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.C. now clear to join nuke waste compact with N.J., Conn.  </HEADLINE>
By LEIGH STROPE
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) - South Carolina no longer will be the final
resting place for most of the nation's low-level nuclear waste, the
governor said Wednesday as he signed legislation to join New Jersey
and Connecticut in a disposal agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''After years of discussion we have finally come up with a
solution to our nuclear waste problem in South Carolina,'' Gov. Jim
Hodges said as he signed the bill into law. The first-term Democrat
had pledged to end what he said was the state's reputation as the
''nation's nuclear dumping ground.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey and Connecticut are expected to grant South
Carolina's petition to join the Atlantic Compact, said John Clark,
a senior aide to Hodges. South Carolina would be admitted July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very pleased that the governor has signed the
legislation,'' said Amy Collings, spokeswoman for the New Jersey
Department of Environmental Protection. ''We look forward to
welcoming South Carolina to the compact.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barnwell County landfill now takes nuclear waste from
throughout the nation. By joining the compact, South Carolina can
accept shipments from only those two states.
</P>
<P>
   With about 3 million cubic feet of storage remaining, state
officials say the Barnwell site would fill in eight to 10 years if
waste kept coming at current rates.
</P>
<P>
   The new law limits New Jersey's and Connecticut's disposal space
to a total of 800,000 cubic feet. That is to ensure enough space
for waste generated when South Carolina's nuclear power plants are
decommissioned in about 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Most of New Jersey's waste comes from medical uses and academic
research, Collings said.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina withdrew from the Southeast Compact Commission in
1995 after then-Gov. David Beasley said he was tired with North
Carolina's failure to build a replacement for the Barnwell
landfill.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina then reopened Barnwell to all other states,
intending to use the increased revenue for education, but the
amount of money never reached projections.
</P>
<P>
   That revenue will decrease, but the law says the Legislature
must maintain the education funding using other state revenue.
</P>
<P>
   By joining the Atlantic Compact amount of low-level nuclear
waste buried at Barnwell would be cut in half by 2002 and continue
to be restricted each year through 2008, Hodges said.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 people now work there for Chem-Nuclear Systems Inc.,
and 15 to 20 employees eventually could lose their jobs, said
Clark, Hodges' aide.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was something people were a little leery of when the
process started,'' said Sen. Brad Hutto, D-Orangeburg.
</P>
<P>
   But the $12 million paid to South Carolina by New Jersey and
Connecticut will help fund economic development projects in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will easily be able to make up for a loss of jobs'' with
the cash infusion, said Barnwell County Councilman Flowe Trexler.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina would have two governor-appointed members on the
compact commission, which would be headquartered here. The other
states would have one each, giving South Carolina veto power.
</P>
<P>
   The new law also creates a Governor's Nuclear Advisory Council
to oversee the Barnwell site and make recommendations on
management, use and handling of nuclear material.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-07-00 2140 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard Crisis Forces Cutbacks  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A financial crisis in the Coast Guard budget
has forced reductions in air and sea operations, resulting in
increased response time in some rescue missions and fewer drug and
migrant interdictions, the Coast Guard Commandant said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Admiral James M. Loy, testifying to the House Transportation
panel on the Coast Guard, said budget constraints have made it
impossible for the Guard to fully carry out its mission. ''It
breaks my heart to say so, but it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Loy also apologized to the subcommittee, chaired by Rep. Wayne
Gilchrest, R-Md., for not telling it earlier that this year's
budget wouldn't be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Congress fully funded the $4.2 billion budget for the Coast
Guard requested by President Clinton for the fiscal year 2000 that
started last October. But that budget did not include money for
military pay increases and other personnel benefits approved in a
separate Defense Department bill.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Loy said, ''$75 million worth of bills have sort of
accrued on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard has deferred maintenance on aircraft and vessels
and diverted funds from law enforcement. In January Loy directed
his Atlantic and Pacific area commanders to reduce cutter days and
flight hours by about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Greater Miami Chamber of Commerce on
Wednesday, the regional commander there warned of drastic
scalebacks if Loy can't get more money from Congress for this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Absent success in obtaining this funding,'' said Rear Admiral
Thad W. Allen, commandant of the 7th Coast Guard District, ''we may
be faced with much deeper cuts that would reduce our law
enforcement presence in the Caribbean by as much as 90 percent for
the remainder of the fiscal year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard has identified a $225 million shortfall for this
fiscal year, including some $71 million in immediate obligations,
according to subcommittee figures. The immediate costs include $18
million in medical expenses, $15 million for housing, $15 million
for recruiting and retention and $7 million for increased fuel
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The House has approved $37 million for the Coast Guard in an
emergency spending bill bogged down in the Senate. The Senate
instead has inserted $262 million in emergency operating expenses
as part of a fiscal year 2001 military construction spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its operating expense pressures, the Coast Guard is also
looking toward the long-term modernization of its cutter and
aircraft fleets. That ''Deepwater Project'' could cost $10 billion
over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Loy said the president's proposed budget of $4.7 billion for
2001, a 14 percent raise, would be adequate to meet the Coast
Guard's basic needs. But he cautioned that new prescription drug
and medical benefits for military retirees contained in a defense
bill now working its way through Congress could again create
problems for Coast Guard accountants.
</P>
<P>
   Gilchrest complained that the Coast Guard did not raise these
issues in recent hearings about next year's budget. ''I don't want
to see these same problems next year,'' he said. ''We cannot put
the public's safety at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: the subcommittee site:
http://www.house.gov/transportation/ctisub2.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 2141 </TRAILER>
