<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sparring Over UN Women's Document  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Women's rights activists accused the
Vatican and some Islamic and Catholic countries of blocking
consensus on a U.N. document to accelerate the drive for equality
of the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of anti-abortion and religious activists countered
that they had far more support for their conservative approach to
women's rights and blamed rich Western states for pushing ''radical
language'' on sexual rights, homosexual rights and abortion for
stalling negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The group released a letter signed by 23 members of the U.S.
Congress expressing ''great alarm'' that the U.S. delegation to
this week's conference is calling for increased access to abortions
and mandatory training to perform them -- and is promoting ''a new
and dangerous term, 'sexual rights.'''
</P>
<P>
   ''It will mean not just special rights for homosexuals but could
mean the right to sexual expression for children. Moreover, it may
allow for the spread of prostitution,'' said the letter, which was
addressed to all 188 U.N. member states.
</P>
<P>
   The charge and counter-charge came just two days before the end
of the week-long meeting to review progress toward women's equality
since the landmark U.N. women's conference in Beijing five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates were meeting in small groups into the night trying to
meet a self-imposed deadline of Thursday afternoon to reach
consensus on a final text.
</P>
<P>
   During months of closed-door negotiations on the final document
before the conference began Monday, delegates said the Vatican and
a handful of Islamic countries including Algeria, Iran, Libya,
Pakistan and Sudan held up action on key issues.
</P>
<P>
   This week, human rights and women's activists and U.N. High
Commissioner for Human Rights Mary Robinson warned against attempts
to roll back the gains from Beijing. And governments from South
Africa to China demanded that the conference adopt a
forward-looking plan to implement the 150-page Beijing platform for
action, which calls for equality in health, education and jobs and
an end to the increasing poverty of women.
</P>
<P>
   Gita Sen, a professor at the Indian Institute of Management who
heads a grassroots women's organization, told a news conference
Wednesday there is ''strong and growing support'' from Latin
America, Africa, Turkey, India, Mexico and many other countries for
a final document that will reaffirm and move forward the Beijing
platform.
</P>
<P>
   But she said at the top of the list of states stalling final
agreement were the Vatican, Nicaragua, Libya, Sudan and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope this hard core will move,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, Sen said, the conference should adopt the final
document by consensus ''so that the tyranny of this miniscule
minority can be ended.'' She said nations opposed to the document
could still express reservations, just as they did at Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time Wednesday, a coalition of conservative
anti-abortion and religious groups held a news conference to
counter what they claimed was ''political spin'' by the West that
only a few countries were holding up negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is a lie,'' said Austin Ruse, president of the Catholic
Family and Human Rights Institute. He said the coalition's position
had broad support, though none of its members named any other
countries who backed its positions.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the impasse on ''radical language being pushed by the
rich Western states.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruse accused the those countries of engaging in ''sexual
colonialism'' which attempts ''to spread through the developing
world the kind of personal immorality that has utterly failed the
rich West.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Glynn, spokeswoman for the U.S. Mission to the United
Nations, countered that the United States believes that access to
family planning and reproductive health information will lead to
fewer abortions in the world -- ''which we support.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the Beijing platform recognized for the first
time that human rights include the right of women to control their
own sexuality without ''coercion, discrimination and violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 2146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
