<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rancher Convicted in Murder Plot  </HEADLINE>
By PETER MUELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Nearly a decade after the murder
of Amazon environmental activist Expedito Ribeiro de Souza, a
Brazilian court convicted a rancher of ordering the killing and
sentenced him to 19{ years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Cheering erupted in the courtroom as Jeronimo Alves Amorim was
sentenced late Tuesday night in the Amazon River port of Belem,
1,400 miles northwest of Rio.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 2, 1991, Souza was leaving union headquarters when he
was shot and killed. His predecessor and several other union
leaders had died the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists protested that officials had done nothing
to protect Souza, despite frequent death threats for his opposition
to the unequal distribution of land and the rampant destruction of
the rain forest by ranchers and loggers.
</P>
<P>
   The international outcry brought results. Gunman Jose Serafim
Sales was convicted of pulling the trigger and sentenced to 24
years in 1995, while Amorim's ranch foreman Francisco de Assis
Ferreira got 20 years for hiring Sales to kill Souza.
</P>
<P>
   Sales later escaped from prison and is at large, while Ferreira
is out on parole.
</P>
<P>
   The conviction could signal a change in Amazon-style justice,
which historically has favored land owners, said Malu Maranhao,
spokeswoman for the Catholic Church's Pastoral Land Commission in
Goiania, near the capital of Brasilia.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,169 victims of land violence documented by the Catholic
church between 1985 and 1998, she said only 86 cases have gone to
trial and just eight defendants accused of ordering a killing have
been convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Land violence is notorious in huge Para state, where 700
farmworkers have been killed in the past 15 years, according to
church figures. Nowhere was it worse than in Rio Maria, a frontier
town some 300 miles south of Belem, where Souza was head of the
Farmworkers Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
