<HEADLINE> Lakers Lead Pacers 33-18 in 1Q  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Shaquille O'Neal, overpowering Rik Smits and
every other Indiana defender who sagged on him, scored 15 points on
7-of-8 shooting Wednesday night as the Los Angeles Lakers took a
33-18 first-quarter lead over the Pacers in the opener of the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's early offensive strategy obviously was to take the
ball inside to Smits and have him go against O'Neal, with the hope
that it might get the Lakers center in foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal did not foul once in the quarter, and he also had
five rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Smits had four points and missed four shots, including an
airball on his first shot of the game, a short hook.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' Kobe Bryant added eight points on 4-of-6 shooting
in the first 12 minutes, including a driving dunk over the 7-foot-4
Smits.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers made 15 of 22 shots (68 percent), while Indiana was
7-of-20 (35 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson hit all three of his shots and scored eight points
for Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller of the Pacers missed all six of his shots and went
scoreless. He had a couple of in-and-outs from 3-point range and he
also failed to score on two drives -- with O'Neal swatting one shot
away and Miller losing control of the ball on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper added eight points and four assists for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal put the Lakers up 5-2 with a basket and free throw with
10:22 left in the first quarter, and Los Angeles continued to open
up the lead.
</P>
