<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former CBS Exec Blair Clark Dies  </HEADLINE>
By NINA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Blair Clark, a former CBS news executive
who also managed Eugene McCarthy's presidential campaign, has died.
He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, heir to the Clark Thread fortune, died Tuesday at
Princeton Medical Center of complications from colon surgery,
according to his son Timothy Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Clark joined CBS News as a foreign correspondent in Paris in
1953 and later anchored the ''The World Tonight'' for CBS Radio
Network.
</P>
<P>
   He became vice president and general manager of CBS News in
1961. While he was in that position, the news broadcast was
expanded from 15 minutes to a half hour -- a first for network
television -- and Walter Cronkite took over as anchor of ''The
Evening News.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Blair brought a high sense of news integrity to the news
business. He made some people uncomfortable -- those who were
inclined to sensationalize,'' Cronkite said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clark began his career in journalism as a reporter for the St.
Louis Post-Dispatch, then spent five years in the U.S. Army during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, he took $60,000 he inherited from his grandmother and
founded The New Hampshire Sunday News. He worked for the Boston
Herald and Traveler before joining CBS.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the network, he served as associate publisher of
the New York Post, then became campaign manager for Democratic
presidential candidate Eugene McCarthy in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Clark worked as a free-lance writer from 1969-1975. He was the
editor of The Nation magazine from 1976-1978.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was born in Easthampton, N.Y., and raised in Princeton. He
attended Harvard University, where he served as editor of the
Harvard Crimson and enlisted John F. Kennedy to work on the college
paper, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Blair Clark was a member of that great generation of American
journalists who saw the onset of the Cold War and reported it for a
generation,'' said Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son Timothy, Clark is survived by his wife
Joanna Rostropowicz, son Ian, stepson Tomasz Malinowksi, a sister
and a brother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 2209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate passes penalty enhancer for hate crimes  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Criminals who select victims on the basis of
their personal characteristics such as race or sexual preference
would face heightened penalties in New York under a bill approved
Wednesday by the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning their longstanding opposition to so-called hate
crimes legislation, Senate Republicans allowed the chamber to vote
on a measure proposed by fellow Republican Gov. George Pataki. It
passed, 48-12.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would boost penalties for more than 50 kinds of crimes
if it can be proven that an offender acted with bias against some
objectionable aspect of a victim when committing the crime. Those
personal characteristics include a victim's age, gender, sexual
orientation, religion, race, disability and country of origin.
</P>
<P>
   The bill calls for people found guilty of hate crimes to be
sentenced to penalties a step higher than their offenses would
normally carry. For instance, a person convicted of a crime that is
a Class E felony - subject to as much as four years in prison -
would be sentenced under the terms of a Class D felony if the
offense was a hate crime, and face up to seven years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   New York is one of nine states without a hate crimes law on the
books, proponents of the bill said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Roy Goodman, a Manhattan Republican, called the hate crimes
bill he has long sponsored a landmark which will combat the
''darkest impulses'' of warped people.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we've done something that is both noble in intent and
practical in application,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Senate's 36 Republicans are usually unanimously in
favor of legislation they allow to reach the floor of their
chamber, there was dissension in the GOP ranks Wednesday. Senators
who blocked the bill in the past argued that singling out some
crimes for higher penalties was unfair to victims of non-bias
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Serphin Maltese, a Queens Republican who once chaired the
state's Conservative Party, said the bill's message seemed to him
like something out of a George Orwell novel - ''We are all equal,
but some are more equal than others.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Should a person, an elderly woman mugged on a street corner,
be afforded less protection ... than those protected under this
statute?'' Maltese asked. ''My reply is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Marchi, R-Staten Island, argued that no one can say
that hate-crime laws have actually worked in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has no demonstrable value,'' Marchi said. ''Nowhere has
this made any difference at all, not one scintilla. Can you cite
one example where this has worked beneficially at diminishing
crime, at diminishing hatred? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Republicans in favor said they had their doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican leader Joseph Bruno said the measure may be
''more perception'' than an effective crime-fighting bill, but he
acknowledged that it may be the right time to send the message
anyway. He voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all 12 senators voting against the bill were
Republicans: John DeFrancisco of Syracuse, Hugh Farley of
Schenectady, John Kuhl Jr. of Steuben County, William Larkin of
Orange County, Thomas Libous of Binghamton, Maltese, Marchi, George
Maziarz of Niagara Falls, Patricia McGee of Chautauqua County,
Michael Nozzolio of Seneca County, Dale Volker of Erie County and
James Wright of Jefferson County.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' 26 votes in favor of the bill were crucial to its
passage.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is unlikely to be the final word on the subject in
2000 by the Legislature. The state Assembly, which has approved
hate crime bills for the past 11 years, passed a more expansive
measure than the Senate version this year.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of bills said they thought the Senate, Assembly
and governor would have little trouble reconciling the differences
in the two bills.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Senate Republicans justified their opposition to
hate crimes bills by arguing that it is unfair to single out one
class of crime victims as being more ''important'' than others
because penalties are higher if they are attacked. Gay and lesbian
groups have long argued that the real source of opposition was
reluctance on the part of the Senate to pass any legislation which
could be seen as sympathetic to homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Gay groups, Jewish anti-defamation organizations and others
jockeyed Wednesday to take credit for being long-standing advocates
of a hate crimes bill and for supposedly putting decisive pressure
on the Senate to finally take up the measure.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, Democratic candidate for U.S.
Senate, said that she appeared in Albany in April specifically to
promote the hate-crimes bill and would push for national
legislation if elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Hevesi, a Queens Democrat, said the bias bill will
not by itself stop bigoted behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not the end,'' he said. ''This will not stop bias
crimes from occurring. We need to educate. ... Nobody's born a
racist. That is a learned behavior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
