<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressJames Balanoff:
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMMOND, Ind. (AP) -- James Balanoff, a former district director
of the United Steelworkers of America and a former Hammond City
Council member, died Monday of complications from a stroke. He was
78.
</P>
<P>
   Belanoff served as director of District 31 of the United
Steelworkers of America from 1977 to 1981. Before that he served a
year as president of Local 1010.
</P>
<P>
   Balanoff was elected to the Hammond City Council and served from
1983 to 1987 and again from 1991 to 1995.
Faygele benMiriam:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Faygele benMiriam, a cross-dressing civil service
worker who won a Supreme Court ruling in a gay rights case, died
Monday of lung cancer. He was 55.
</P>
<P>
   BenMiriam helped found the city's Gay Community Social Services
in 1971 and produced the gay country music album ''Lavendar
Country.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, he and his partner at the time, became the first couple
to apply for a same-sex marriage license.
</P>
<P>
   BenMiriam lost that case and, the next year, was fired from his
job as a clerk-typist at the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission largely because he was gay and wore capes and dresses to
work.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union took his case and in 1978,
the Supreme Court ordered the commission to reconsider his firing
in light of new regulations, enacted in 1975, which specified that
no one could be disqualified from federal employment solely on the
basis of sexual orientation. BenMiriam received back pay but chose
to work for the U.S. Department of Labor.
Blair Clark:
</P>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Blair Clark, a former CBS news executive
who also managed Eugene McCarthy's presidential campaign, died
Tuesday of complications from colon surgery. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, heir to the Clark Thread fortune, worked in both print
and broadcast journalism. He joined CBS News as a foreign
correspondent in Paris in 1953 and later anchored the ''The World
Tonight'' for CBS Radio Network.
</P>
<P>
   He became vice president and general manager of CBS News in
1961.
</P>
<P>
   Clark began his career in journalism as a reporter for the St.
Louis Post-Dispatch, then spent five years in the U.S. Army during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, he took $60,000 he inherited from his grandmother and
founded The New Hampshire Sunday News. Clark worked for the Boston
Herald and Traveler before joining CBS.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the network, he had a stint as associate publisher
of the New York Post before becoming campaign manager for
Democratic presidential candidate Eugene McCarthy in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Clark worked as a free-lance writer from 1969-75. He was the
editor of The Nation magazine from 1976-78.
</P>
<P>
   While at Harvard University, Clark served as editor of the
Harvard Crimson and enlisted John F. Kennedy to work on the college
paper, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son Timothy, Clark is survived by his wife
Joanna Rostropowicz, son Ian, stepson Tomasz Malinowksi, a sister
and a brother.
Don Klosterman:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Don Klosterman, a general manager in three
professional football leagues with such teams as the San Diego
Chargers, Houston Oilers, Baltimore Colts and Los Angeles Rams,
died Tuesday. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   A former pro quarterback, Klosterman was involved in the growth
of the American Football League with the Chargers in the 1960s,
prior to the AFL merger with the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Klosterman was the Rams' vice president and general manager in
Los Angeles from 1972-80.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '80s, he became the president and general manager
of the Los Angeles Express of the United States Football League.
Walter Poenisch:
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Walter Poenisch, the first person to swim
from Cuba to Florida, died Tuesday after a long illness. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   He made a 128.8-mile swim across the Florida Straits in 1978,
when he was 64.
</P>
<P>
   Using flippers on his feet, he took 34 hours and 15 minutes for
the crossing from Havana, where Cuban President Fidel Castro gave
him a send-off.
</P>
<P>
   The International Swimming Hall of Fame in Fort Lauderdale,
Fla., refused to recognize his feat because he got out of the water
once during the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Poenisch said the 12-minute interruption was for medical
treatment, which is permitted. He sued the hall of fame and its
officials and won a $1.5 million settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Poenisch's swim was recognized elsewhere, including the Guinness
Book of Records and the International Federation of Professional
Oceanic Swimmers and Divers.
Thomas Edward Quinlan:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Thomas Edward Quinlan, a business reporter
for the San Jose Mercury News, died. The medical examiner's office
on Wednesday had not determined a time or cause of death. He was
44.
</P>
<P>
   Quinlan had chronicled the Silicon Valley's microchip industry
for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Quinlan grew up covering high tech, first for Computer Reseller
News, where he started work in the mid-1980s, and InfoWorld before
joining the Mercury News.
</P>
<P>
   He was cited for his coverage of the Federal Trade Commission's
investigation of Intel and a two-part series that ran last year
examining how Intel, a mere chip maker, came to dominate the entire
computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Quinlan's survivors include three sisters and several nieces and
nephews.
Sanford Stephens:
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Sanford ''Sandy'' Stephens, a former
All-America quarterback who led Minnesota to its only Rose Bowl
victory, was found dead Tuesday of an apparent heart attack. He was
59.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens was a four-sport athlete from Uniontown, Pa. He turned
down professional baseball to play football at Minnesota, and
became the first black quarterback for the Gophers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens led Minnesota to an 8-2 record and a national title in
1960.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1962 Rose Bowl, Stephens scored two touchdowns as the
Gophers beat UCLA 21-3.
David D. Van Tassel:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- David D. Van Tassel, a retired history
professor and founder of the National History Day competition, died
Saturday of a heart attack. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Van Tassel was on the faculty at the university from 1969 until
his retirement in 1998. He taught at the University of Texas from
1961 to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, he founded History Day in the Cleveland area to
encourage historical research and learning among high school
students through an event modeled after science fairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
