<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dismissals Sought in Columbine Suits  </HEADLINE>
By P. SOLOMON BANDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Jefferson County attorneys asked a federal judge
Wednesday to dismiss four lawsuits filed by families of Columbine
victims saying the lawsuits unfairly blame the sheriff's department
for the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although it is natural to assign blame after a tragedy of this
magnitude, the law does not support the attempts to blame law
enforcement officers and government officials for atrocities
committed by Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold,'' assistant county
attorney William Tuthill said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Tuthill said dismissal motions were filed Wednesday. He did not
return a phone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Families of 10 victims of the April 20, 1999, shootings at
Columbine High School have sued in federal court, alleging that
sheriff's deputies failed to act fast enough to rescue the students
and a wounded teacher who later died and failed to properly train
deputies, dispatchers and 911 operators.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold fatally shot 12 students and a teacher before
committing suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits also state that the sheriff's department could have
prevented the tragedy by investigating threats made on Harris' Web
site against another Columbine student more than a year before the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rouse, an attorney for families of five of the shooting
victims, said he was not surprised by the county's action.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not suing the Jefferson County sheriff for what the two
gunmen did. We are suing because of how the sheriff's department
handled the response,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Jefferson County attorney's office said a
report issued last month by the sheriff's department showed
officers performed ''both appropriately and admirably.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the federal lawsuits, the families of five
Columbine victims have lawsuits pending in state court.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://jeffcosheriff.com
</P>
</TEXT>
