<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Magnitude 6.2 Quake Rocks Indonesia  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL COONEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENGKULU, Indonesia (AP) -- For the father of 8-year-old Theresia
Kurniasari, one of Indonesia's earthquake victims, the only
consolation is that she was sleeping when she died.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred friends and relatives from the rubble-strewn town of
Bengkulu, many nursing injuries, paid their last respects Wednesday
to the little girl in a pink dress lying in an open coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the magnitude 7.9 quake devastated communities
on the island of Sumatra, Theresia was laid to rest with a simple
funeral service in a Methodist church.
</P>
<P>
   ''A wall collapsed on her,'' said the father, Djunaidy, who like
many Indonesians goes by only one name. ''Her aunt carried her from
the house, but when they tried to wake her she was asleep. Jesus
had called her soul to heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, a magnitude 6.2 earthquake rocked the region but
there were no immediate reports of new damage or injuries, the
Indonesian Meteorological and Geophysical Service reported.
</P>
<P>
   The new quake hit at 6.45 a.m. Thursday and was centered about
125 miles southeast of Bengkulu in the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the lastest quake, about 100 homeless people blocked
a key road near the town protesting what they said was a slow
government response to the disaster. About 30 police struggled to
diffuse tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government is no good. No aid has reached here yet. We
need tents food and medicine,'' said Yudi, 40, a protester going by
just one name. His 5-year old son was injured in the quake and his
home flattened.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims and Christians who live in this quake-prone corner of
the Indonesian island chain are picking through the wreckage of
their ruined homes as they mourn their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   With telephone lines down and roads torn apart by crevasses,
nobody is sure exactly how many died in the quake late Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Local media reported 117 dead, but hospital staff and police put
the number of fatalities lower. An emergency government task force
reported 94 dead, 930 badly hurt and 934 slightly hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Residents whose homes are intact are afraid to sleep inside and
face a fourth night outdoors. Hundreds of aftershocks followed the
initial quake, which was felt in Indonesia's capital, Jakarta, more
than 310 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of the simple houses in Bengkulu and small towns that
line the quake-cracked road along the Indian Ocean coastline either
have been flattened or badly damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency relief arrived in Bengkulu on Wednesday. Military
planes and warships brought medicine, tents and food. Singapore,
the United States, Australia, Japan and Thailand have pledged aid.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations and Red Cross staff were hampered by heavy rain
as they tried to assess the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Two Dutch vessels and one Indonesian navy ship were set to
deliver food and medicine by helicopter Thursday to badly hit
Enggano Island, near the quake's epicenter in the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 refugees from Enggano, home to 1,800 people, crossed
to Bengkulu on Wednesday and said they had lost everything and
urgently needed food and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Personnel from two other Dutch navy ships and one frigate from
Belgium were set to help restore electricity and rebuild Bengkulu's
hospital, which is swamped with casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons were performing operations under shelters fashioned
from old parachutes. Dozens of injured people took refuge under
leaky plastic sheets in the hospital parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need medical supplies, we need more tents. We need blood
and operating equipment,'' said Dr. Ahmad Budiono. Health officials
also feared a scarcity of clean water might trigger disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 2311 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000607.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockers 83, Miracle 79  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Eva Nemcova tied her career high with 23 points
and Chastity Melvin scored six of her 22 in overtime as the
Cleveland Rockers beat the Orlando Miracle 83-79 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the third straight for the Rockers (3-1), who
only won seven games all last season and had never beaten Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The Miracle moved out to a 19-8 lead with 14:08 left in the
first half, but Cleveland responded with a 16-2 run to go ahead.
There were 16 ties and nine lead changes overall.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando (3-2) led 43-41 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando's Nykesha Sales (game-high 24 points) opened the second
half by hitting a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   An 8-0 run put the Miracle up 60-50, but the Rockers cut the
lead when Suzie McConnell Serio and Nemcova hit consecutive
3-pointers as the team went on a 10-0 run to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando's Adrienne Johnson broke the 73-73 tie in overtime with
a layup. The Rockers tied it up again when Melvin hit two free
throws. Taj McWilliams then made a driving layup for the Miracle
but two bad passes allowed Cleveland to score and pull ahead 79-77.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson hit an 18-foot jumper to tie the game 79-79. Sales threw
a bad pass, and Nemcova hit a 3-pointer to put the Rockers up for
good.
</P>
<P>
   Merlakia Jones had 10 points and four rebounds for the Rockers.
</P>
<P>
   Sales went 4-for-5 on 3-pointers and grabbed six rebounds for
Orlando. McWilliams had 16 points and eight rebounds, while Cintia
dos Santos had 11 points and Shannon Johnson 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
