<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN, OAU To Probe Togo Executions  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations announced Wednesday it
was launching an investigation into the deaths of hundreds of
people in Togo in 1998, allegedly at the hands of the country's
notoriously repressive paramilitary police and armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation will be carried out jointly with the
Organization of African Unity and is being conducted with the full
support of the Togolese government, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard said it was premature to speculate about whether the
probe would recommend punishment for the perpetrators. Previous
U.N. commissions of inquiry -- for Rwanda and more recently East
Timor -- have resulted in calls for an international criminal
tribunal to bring to justice those resposible for mass killings.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International last year documented what it called a
pattern of repression in Togo under its dictator-turned-president,
Gnassingbe Eyadema. The human rights group said repression reached
a high after June 1998 elections, when Eyadema prematurely ended
ballot counting and declared himself the winner.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote results were announced, hundreds of people,
including members of the military, were killed by the security
forces, Amnesty said in the May report. Corpses were washed up on
the beaches of Togo and neighboring Benin for days afterward, it
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the report was released, the Togolese government announced
it would take legal action against the human rights organization.
But after international pressure mounted on Eyadema, the government
consented to an international investigation into the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Togo, his statement said, has promised to cooperate fully with
the investigation, which is expected to begin ''in the near
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 2320 </TRAILER>
