<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Highlights His Role in Economy  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore is making a ''progress
and prosperity tour'' through battleground states to spotlight his
plans to keep America's booming economy going as voters appear
split on whether he would do any better than George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The planned tour, which the Democratic presidential candidate is
to begin next week, is meant to fuel his aggressive drive to define
his image -- and his message -- in positive and upbeat terms. At the
same time, Gore plans to begin rolling out a series of new domestic
policy addresses, starting with a speech next Tuesday on a proposal
to protect the future of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to make our campaign about ideas, not insults, because
we have an important story to tell the American people -- about the
dreams we have realized and the work that's still undone, about how
far we have come these past seven years and how much farther is
left to go,'' Gore said Wednesday, previewing this theme at a
Democratic Party fund-raiser in Palm Springs, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In the Medicare speech, Gore will propose putting the payroll
taxes that fund a portion of the health care program ''off budget,
off line and into an ironclad lock box'' so that Congress can't use
the money for tax cuts or other spending, campaign spokesman Chris
Lehane said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the late 80s and early 90s, one of the challenges that
faced Social Security was that Republicans were constantly
raiding'' its surpluses, Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to ensure that as the government collect more money
than needed to fund Medicare, which provides health care to about
40 million elderly and disabled people, those surplus funds are
used only to pay down the national debt. Gore believes doing so
also would help hold down interest rates and keep the economy
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The big issue in this campaign is who is going to maintain
economic security, and taking Medicare off budget is the next
logical step in ensuring long-term economic security,'' Lehane
added.
</P>
<P>
   The details of Gore's Medicare proposal were first reported by
the Washington Post in a story posted on its Web site Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials, meanwhile, said the tour would last at
least a week and possibly stretch to two, hitting Kentucky,
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Wisconsin and other key battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   The public is not yet convinced Gore is the best choice to keep
the nation's strong economy going after an unprecedented 1990s
expansion. Polls indicate voters are about evenly divided on
whether Gore or Bush, the two-term Texas governor, is the best
candidate to continue the boom.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial and political analysts suggest the high-tech
economy and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan should get the
credit rather than President Clinton or Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is so clearly happening with Gore is that he is not
getting credit for the economy,'' said Stephen Hess, a senior
fellow at the Brookings Institution. ''Economic indicators are
almost always good predictors of a presidential election.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has trailed Bush by 5 to 10 points in many national polls,
though recent surveys suggest the race may be closing five months
ahead of Election Day. Bush also has a commanding lead in the
state-by-state contest, according to polls.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, in policy speeches, has promised to keep the
country's economy growing by investing the surplus in popular
programs like Social Security and by paying down the debt. Gore
refers to the highly regarded former Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin as ''my tutor'' and refers frequently to Bush's ''risky
schemes'' for deep tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign swing comes as the Democratic Party launches
pro-Gore ads in 15 states, including in battlegrounds such as Ohio,
Pennsylvania, Michigan, Illinois, Missouri and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do think it's a good move,'' said Eric Rademacher,
co-director of the Ohio Poll at the University of Cincinnati.
''Stressing the economy would be a positive -- anything that Gore
can do to bring some more favorable images to his candidacy and the
campaign would help.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore trails Bush by 9 points in Ohio, a state Rademacher noted
has gone for the winner in all but two presidential elections in
the last century.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that issues such as the economy, Social Security and
health care are uppermost in voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans suggest Gore's economic pitch may fall flat.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's questionable whether his message that he is responsible
for the nation's prosperity and good financial times will sell in
middle America,'' said Leslie Gromis, an adviser to Republican Gov.
Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania. ''Voters have come to see the vice
president as somebody who is willing to say anything and take
credit for anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-07-00 2326 </TRAILER>
