<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Up by Six Heading Into 4Q  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Shaquille O'Neal had 10 points in the third
quarter after scoring 21 in the first half and the Los Angeles
Lakers held a 77-71 lead over the Indiana Pacers heading into the
fourth quarter of the NBA Finals opener Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, who fell behind early and trailed by double digits
much of the first three quarters, rallied from a 67-51 deficit to
close within 71-69 on Mark Jackson's jumper with 1:30 remaining in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   But Indiana didn't score again in the period, while Kobe Bryant
scored on two drives and Brian Shaw, who had missed three earlier
3-point tries, made one with two seconds left in the quarter to
give the Lakers some breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers center Rik Smits also drew his fourth and fifth fouls on
one Lakers' possession in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's Reggie Miller, who missed seven shots and went
scoreless in the first half, finally got his first points with two
free throws 3:45 into the third period. He added his first field
goal some three minutes later, on a short bank shot.
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter was the second time the Pacers had made a run,
only to see the Lakers pull away.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were up 33-18 at the end of the opening quarter, but
Indiana started the second with a rush.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Travis Best, the Pacers reeled off a 13-4 streak,
narrowing the gap to 37-31 four minutes into the period. Best hit
two jumpers and fed Jalen Rose for a 3-pointer to spur the Pacers'
spurt to begin the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Los Angeles coach Phil Jackson called for a timeout and the
Lakers responded with an 11-2 run over the next four minutes to
open the lead back to 48-33. They led 55-43 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, O'Neal went 10-of-14 from the field and had
seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Croshere came off the bench to lead the Pacers with 11
points first-half points, nine in the second quarter, and Rose had
10.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's offensive strategy in the first quarter was to take
the ball inside to Smits and have him go against O'Neal, with the
hope that it might get the Lakers center in foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The plan didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, overpowering Smits and every other Indiana defender who
sagged on him, scored 15 points on 7-of-8 shooting as the Lakers
led by 15 after the first quarter. O'Neal did not commit foul in
the period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
